- Thank you for having me,
I'm excited to be here.

00:07:06.640 --> 00:07:09.510
- Yeah, I have a lot of questions for you.

00:07:09.510 --> 00:07:13.560
I, and many listeners of this podcast,

00:07:13.560 --> 00:07:17.750
are obsessed with dopamine,
and what is dopamine,

00:07:17.750 --> 00:07:18.583
how does it work?

00:07:18.583 --> 00:07:20.730
We all hear that dopamine is this molecule

00:07:20.730 --> 00:07:22.790
associated with pleasure.

00:07:22.790 --> 00:07:25.700
I think the term dopamine hits,

00:07:25.700 --> 00:07:28.850
like I'm getting a dopamine
hit from this, from Instagram,

00:07:28.850 --> 00:07:31.620
or from likes or from
praise or from whatever,

00:07:31.620 --> 00:07:35.053
is now commonly heard.

00:07:36.010 --> 00:07:37.760
What is dopamine,

00:07:37.760 --> 00:07:40.510
and what are maybe some
things about dopamine

00:07:40.510 --> 00:07:42.040
that most people don't know?

00:07:42.040 --> 00:07:44.860
And probably that I don't know either.

00:07:44.860 --> 00:07:47.220
- So dopamine is a neurotransmitter,

00:07:47.220 --> 00:07:49.490
and neurotransmitters are those molecules

00:07:49.490 --> 00:07:52.780
that bridge the gap between two neurons.

00:07:52.780 --> 00:07:55.080
So they essentially allow one neuron,

00:07:55.080 --> 00:07:56.760
the pre-synaptic neuron,

00:07:56.760 --> 00:07:59.750
to communicate with the
post-synaptic neuron.

00:07:59.750 --> 00:08:03.300
Dopamine is intimately associated

00:08:03.300 --> 00:08:06.950
with the experience of reward,
but also with movement,

00:08:06.950 --> 00:08:08.360
which I think is really interesting,

00:08:08.360 --> 00:08:10.990
because movement and
reward are linked, right?

00:08:10.990 --> 00:08:14.600
If you think about,
you know, early humans,

00:08:14.600 --> 00:08:18.700
you had to move in order
to go seek out the water

00:08:18.700 --> 00:08:21.640
or the meat or whatever it was.

00:08:21.640 --> 00:08:24.450
And even in the most primitive organisms,

00:08:24.450 --> 00:08:27.600
dopamine is released when food
is sensed in the environment.

00:08:27.600 --> 00:08:31.763
For example, C elegans,
a very primitive worm.

00:08:32.900 --> 00:08:36.810
So dopamine is this really powerful,

00:08:36.810 --> 00:08:39.910
important molecule in the brain

00:08:39.910 --> 00:08:43.410
that helps us experience pleasure.

00:08:43.410 --> 00:08:46.160
It's not the only neurotransmitter
involved in pleasure,

00:08:46.160 --> 00:08:48.631
but it's a really, really important one.

00:08:48.631 --> 00:08:51.460
And if you want to think about something

00:08:51.460 --> 00:08:53.500
that most people don't
know about dopamine,

00:08:53.500 --> 00:08:54.790
which I think is really interesting,

00:08:54.790 --> 00:08:57.970
is that we are always releasing dopamine

00:08:57.970 --> 00:09:00.750
at a kind of tonic baseline rate.

00:09:00.750 --> 00:09:04.280
And it's really the
deviation from that baseline,

00:09:04.280 --> 00:09:07.020
rather than like hits
of dopamine in a vacuum,

00:09:07.020 --> 00:09:08.220
that make a difference.

00:09:08.220 --> 00:09:10.230
So when we experience pleasure,

00:09:10.230 --> 00:09:13.040
our dopamine release goes above baseline,

00:09:13.040 --> 00:09:17.200
and likewise dopamine can go
below that tonic baseline,

00:09:17.200 --> 00:09:19.960
and then we experience a kind of pain.

00:09:19.960 --> 00:09:20.793
- Interesting.

00:09:20.793 --> 00:09:24.980
So is it fair to say that one's
baseline levels of dopamine,

00:09:24.980 --> 00:09:27.900
how frequently we are releasing dopamine,

00:09:27.900 --> 00:09:30.570
in the absence of some, I don't know,

00:09:30.570 --> 00:09:34.623
drug or food or experience,
just sitting, being,

00:09:35.640 --> 00:09:38.290
is that associated with
how happy somebody is,

00:09:38.290 --> 00:09:41.660
their kind of baseline of
happiness or level of depression?

00:09:41.660 --> 00:09:46.270
- There is evidence that shows
that people who are depressed

00:09:46.270 --> 00:09:51.270
may indeed have lower
tonic levels of dopamine.

00:09:51.350 --> 00:09:53.880
So that's a really reasonable thought,

00:09:53.880 --> 00:09:57.710
and there is some evidence to
suggest that that may be true.

00:09:57.710 --> 00:09:58.757
The other thing that we know,

00:09:58.757 --> 00:10:03.757
and this is really kind
of what the book is about,

00:10:04.430 --> 00:10:08.760
is that if we expose ourselves chronically

00:10:08.760 --> 00:10:11.280
to substances or behaviors

00:10:11.280 --> 00:10:15.630
that repeatedly release
large amounts of dopamine

00:10:15.630 --> 00:10:17.200
in our brains reward pathway,

00:10:17.200 --> 00:10:20.220
that we can change our tonic baseline

00:10:20.220 --> 00:10:22.530
and actually lower it over time,

00:10:22.530 --> 00:10:26.240
as our brain tries to compensate
for all of that dopamine,

00:10:26.240 --> 00:10:31.240
which is more really than we
were designed to experience.

00:10:31.270 --> 00:10:32.660
- Interesting and is,

00:10:32.660 --> 00:10:35.960
is it the case that our
baseline levels of dopamine

00:10:35.960 --> 00:10:39.150
are set by our genetics, by our heredity?

00:10:39.150 --> 00:10:41.507
- Well I think, you know,
if you think about sort of,

00:10:41.507 --> 00:10:44.480
you know, the early stages
of development and infancy,

00:10:44.480 --> 00:10:45.950
certainly that is true.

00:10:45.950 --> 00:10:49.173
You're kind of, you know,
born with probably whatever is

00:10:49.173 --> 00:10:50.320
your baseline level.

00:10:50.320 --> 00:10:54.660
But obviously your experiences
can have a huge impact

00:10:54.660 --> 00:10:59.660
on where your dopamine level
ultimately settles out.

00:11:00.514 --> 00:11:03.110
- So if somebody's disposition is one of

00:11:04.080 --> 00:11:08.060
constant excitement and
anticipation, or easily excited,

00:11:08.060 --> 00:11:10.410
I think about the kind of
people where you say hey,

00:11:10.410 --> 00:11:12.240
do you want to check out
this new place for tacos,

00:11:12.240 --> 00:11:13.320
and they're like "Yeah, that'd be great!"

00:11:13.320 --> 00:11:17.720
And other people are a little
more cynical, harder to budge.

00:11:17.720 --> 00:11:19.323
Like my bulldog Costello.

00:11:20.660 --> 00:11:23.220
Very, very stable, low levels of dopamine

00:11:23.220 --> 00:11:25.023
with big inflections in his case.

00:11:27.109 --> 00:11:31.700
Do you think that's set
in terms of our parents,

00:11:31.700 --> 00:11:36.650
and obviously nature and
nurture interact, but is that,

00:11:36.650 --> 00:11:39.123
is dopamine at the core
of our temperament?

00:11:40.270 --> 00:11:42.990
- I don't really think we
know the answer to that,

00:11:42.990 --> 00:11:47.360
but I will say that people
are definitely born with

00:11:47.360 --> 00:11:52.360
different temperaments, and
those temperaments do affect

00:11:52.560 --> 00:11:55.330
