in many different ways.

00:12:00.430 --> 00:12:02.790
One of the ways that we
describe that in the modern era

00:12:02.790 --> 00:12:05.210
is to use psychiatric nomenclature.

00:12:05.210 --> 00:12:08.520
Like this person has a dysthymic
temperament, or, you know,

00:12:08.520 --> 00:12:11.523
this person has chronic
major depressive disorder.

00:12:12.620 --> 00:12:14.300
In terms of looking specifically

00:12:14.300 --> 00:12:17.460
at who's vulnerable to addiction,

00:12:17.460 --> 00:12:19.760
that's an interesting sort of mixed bag

00:12:19.760 --> 00:12:22.170
because when you look at the research

00:12:22.170 --> 00:12:24.180
on risk factors for addiction,

00:12:24.180 --> 00:12:26.950
so what kind of temperament of a person

00:12:26.950 --> 00:12:29.120
makes them more vulnerable to addiction,

00:12:29.120 --> 00:12:31.270
you see some interesting findings.

00:12:31.270 --> 00:12:33.950
First you see that people
who are more impulsive

00:12:33.950 --> 00:12:35.460
are more vulnerable to addiction.

00:12:35.460 --> 00:12:37.060
So what is impulsivity?

00:12:37.060 --> 00:12:40.450
That means having difficulty
putting space between

00:12:40.450 --> 00:12:42.890
the thought or desire to do something,

00:12:42.890 --> 00:12:44.260
and actually doing it.

00:12:44.260 --> 00:12:47.700
And people who have difficulty
putting a space there,

00:12:47.700 --> 00:12:48.900
who have a thought to do something

00:12:48.900 --> 00:12:51.480
and just do it impulsively,

00:12:51.480 --> 00:12:53.960
are people who are more
vulnerable to addiction.

00:12:53.960 --> 00:12:54.793
- Interesting.

00:12:54.793 --> 00:12:57.060
Could I, in terms of impulsivity,

00:12:57.060 --> 00:12:59.340
is this something that relates literally

00:12:59.340 --> 00:13:01.130
to the startle reflex?

00:13:01.130 --> 00:13:03.700
Like I, for instance, as a lab director,

00:13:03.700 --> 00:13:06.960
I'm familiar with walking
around my lab and when I decide,

00:13:06.960 --> 00:13:08.290
deciding I'm going to talk to my people,

00:13:08.290 --> 00:13:10.500
of course when they knock on
my door it's always like wait,

00:13:10.500 --> 00:13:11.930
why am I being bothered right now?

00:13:11.930 --> 00:13:13.020
Even though I love to talk to them.

00:13:13.020 --> 00:13:14.627
But I walk around my
lab from time to time,

00:13:14.627 --> 00:13:18.440
and some people I notice, I'll
say, do you have a moment,

00:13:18.440 --> 00:13:20.780
and they'll slowly turn
around and say, yeah,

00:13:20.780 --> 00:13:22.293
or no, in some cases.

00:13:23.520 --> 00:13:26.170
And other people will jump
the moment I say their name.

00:13:26.170 --> 00:13:30.750
They actually have a, a kind
of a heightened startle reflex.

00:13:30.750 --> 00:13:32.350
Is that related to impulsivity,

00:13:32.350 --> 00:13:34.630
or is what you're referring to

00:13:34.630 --> 00:13:38.930
an attempt to withhold behavior
that's very deliberate,

00:13:38.930 --> 00:13:40.490
under very deliberate conditions?

00:13:40.490 --> 00:13:43.240
- Yeah, so I don't think
that that startle reflex

00:13:43.240 --> 00:13:45.630
is necessarily related to impulsivity.

00:13:45.630 --> 00:13:47.400
That can be related to anxiety.

00:13:47.400 --> 00:13:49.550
So people who are high anxiety people

00:13:49.550 --> 00:13:52.190
will tend to have more
of a startle reflex.

00:13:52.190 --> 00:13:54.280
Impulsivity is a little bit different.

00:13:54.280 --> 00:13:57.960
And by the way, impulsivity
is not always bad, right.

00:13:57.960 --> 00:14:00.680
Impulsivity is that thing

00:14:00.680 --> 00:14:04.610
where there's not a lot of self-editing

00:14:04.610 --> 00:14:08.003
or worrying about future consequences.

00:14:08.003 --> 00:14:11.010
You know, you have the idea
to do something and you do it.

00:14:11.010 --> 00:14:14.020
And of course we can
imagine many scenarios

00:14:14.020 --> 00:14:16.233
where that's absolutely wonderful.

00:14:17.070 --> 00:14:18.980
You know, there can be a sort of,

00:14:18.980 --> 00:14:23.980
let's say intimate
interactions between people,

00:14:24.030 --> 00:14:25.660
where you wouldn't really want to be

00:14:25.660 --> 00:14:27.110
super inhibited about it, right.

00:14:27.110 --> 00:14:30.680
You would want to be
disinhibited and impulsive.

00:14:30.680 --> 00:14:32.760
I can also like imagine like

00:14:32.760 --> 00:14:35.060
sort of fight or flight scenarios,

00:14:35.060 --> 00:14:36.790
like battle scenarios, right,

00:14:36.790 --> 00:14:39.710
where it would really
be good to be impulsive

00:14:39.710 --> 00:14:41.560
and just go rhino!

00:14:41.560 --> 00:14:43.013
- Where hesitation can cost you your life?

00:14:43.013 --> 00:14:44.940
- Right, yes, that's right, that's right.

00:14:44.940 --> 00:14:46.000
But, you know,

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:47.923
and I think this brings up a really,

00:14:49.098 --> 00:14:51.050
something that I've come to believe

00:14:51.050 --> 00:14:54.290
after 25 years of practicing psychiatry,

00:14:54.290 --> 00:14:59.290
is that what we now conceptualize
in our current ecosystem

00:14:59.554 --> 00:15:02.182
as mental illness,

00:15:02.182 --> 00:15:06.500
are actually traits that
in another ecosystem

00:15:06.500 --> 00:15:08.630
might be very advantageous.

00:15:08.630 --> 00:15:11.610
They're just not advantageous right now,

00:15:11.610 --> 00:15:13.380
because of the world that we live in.

00:15:13.380 --> 00:15:15.070
And I think, you know,

00:15:15.070 --> 00:15:18.230
impulsivity is potentially
one of those, right?

00:15:18.230 --> 00:15:20.580
'Cause we live in this
world that's sort of like,

00:15:20.580 --> 00:15:25.580
you have to constantly be
thinking sort of rationally about

00:15:27.260 --> 00:15:29.620
the consequences of X, Y, or Z.

00:15:29.620 --> 00:15:32.620
And it's such a sensory
rich environment, right,

00:15:32.620 --> 00:15:36.130
that we're being bombarded with
all of these opportunities,

00:15:36.130 --> 00:15:37.720
these sensory opportunities.

00:15:37.720 --> 00:15:39.670
And we have to constantly check ourselves.

00:15:39.670 --> 00:15:43.760
And so impulsivity is
something that right now

00:15:43.760 --> 00:15:45.610
can be a difficult trait,

00:15:45.610 --> 00:15:48.530
but isn't in and of itself a bad thing.

00:15:48.530 --> 00:15:49.580
- I see.

00:15:49.580 --> 00:15:51.890
And it's, I'm beginning to
realize it's a fine line

00:15:51.890 --> 00:15:54.028
between spontaneity and impulsivity.

00:15:54.028 --> 00:15:54.861
- Yeah.

00:15:56.470 --> 00:15:59.750
- What is pleasure and how does it work,

00:15:59.750 --> 00:16:03.470
at the biological level,
and if it feels right,

00:16:03.470 --> 00:16:05.800
at the psychological level?

00:16:05.800 --> 00:16:10.030
And if you don't mind
painting a picture of sort of

00:16:10.030 --> 00:16:15.030
the range of things that you
have observed in your clinic,

00:16:15.290 --> 00:16:18.510
or in life, that people
can become addicted to.

00:16:18.510 --> 00:16:20.470
But just to start off really simply,

00:16:20.470 --> 00:16:23.180
what is this thing that we call pleasure?

00:16:23.180 --> 00:16:26.990
- Well, I think it's actually
really hard to define pleasure

00:16:26.990 --> 00:16:29.130
in any kind of succinct way,

00:16:29.130 --> 00:16:32.927
because certainly there is
the seeking out of a high,

00:16:35.020 --> 00:16:37.810
or a euphoria, or I think, you know,

00:16:37.810 --> 00:16:41.260
the kind of experience that
almost anybody would associate

00:16:41.260 --> 00:16:42.940
with the word pleasure.

00:16:42.940 --> 00:16:45.960
But also the seeking out

00:16:45.960 --> 00:16:48.740
of those same substances and behaviors

00:16:48.740 --> 00:16:51.700
is often a way to escape pain.

00:16:51.700 --> 00:16:55.393
So for example, when I talk
to people with addiction,

00:16:56.960 --> 00:17:01.960
sometimes their initial
foray into using a drug

00:17:01.980 --> 00:17:03.980
is to get pleasure,

00:17:03.980 --> 00:17:07.640
but very often it's a way
to escape their suffering,

00:17:07.640 --> 00:17:09.450
whatever their suffering may be.

00:17:09.450 --> 00:17:12.870
And certainly as people become addicted,

00:17:12.870 --> 00:17:16.010
even those who initially
were seeking out pleasure

00:17:16.010 --> 00:17:19.130
are ultimately just
trying to avoid the pain

00:17:19.130 --> 00:17:22.490
of withdrawal or the
pain of the consequences

00:17:22.490 --> 00:17:23.720
of their drug use.

00:17:23.720 --> 00:17:28.720
So I think it's, you know, very
hard to actually, you know,

00:17:28.740 --> 00:17:30.903
define it as this unitary thing.

00:17:31.866 --> 00:17:33.940
And it's certainly not
just getting a high.

00:17:33.940 --> 00:17:36.870
There are so many ways in which people

00:17:36.870 --> 00:17:38.560
sort of want to escape,

00:17:38.560 --> 00:17:41.810
which is not the same thing
as sort of this hedonic,

00:17:41.810 --> 00:17:43.700
you know, wanting to feel pleasure.

00:17:43.700 --> 00:17:46.570
- So someone could decide that
they want to go out and dance,

00:17:46.570 --> 00:17:49.060
or get up and dance, because
of the pleasure of dancing.

00:17:49.060 --> 00:17:50.193
I can imagine that.

00:17:51.890 --> 00:17:56.160
But, and maybe it's very
difficult for them to stay seated

00:17:56.160 --> 00:17:59.260
when a particular song
comes on, for instance.

00:17:59.260 --> 00:18:03.650
But seeking what we would call pleasure

00:18:03.650 --> 00:18:05.430
in order to eliminate pain,

00:18:05.430 --> 00:18:07.360
that evokes a different
picture in my mind.

00:18:07.360 --> 00:18:11.400
That evokes a picture of
somebody that feels lost

00:18:11.400 --> 00:18:13.523
or depressed or underwhelmed.

00:18:15.010 --> 00:18:17.440
I definitely want to get into the precise

00:18:17.440 --> 00:18:20.100
and general description of
addiction and what that is,

00:18:20.100 --> 00:18:22.070
but in a previous conversation we had,

00:18:22.070 --> 00:18:23.690
you said something that
really rung in my mind,

00:18:23.690 --> 00:18:27.960
which is that many people who
become addicted to things,

00:18:27.960 --> 00:18:29.160
let's call them addicts,

00:18:30.440 --> 00:18:35.320
have this feeling that normal
life isn't interesting enough.

00:18:35.320 --> 00:18:39.100
That they are seeking a
super normal experience,

00:18:39.100 --> 00:18:42.340
and that the day-to-day routine balance,

00:18:42.340 --> 00:18:44.297
which is actually in
the title of your book,

00:18:44.297 --> 00:18:47.320
"Dopamine Nation, Finding Balance
in the Age of Indulgence",

00:18:47.320 --> 00:18:52.320
that the word balance itself
can sometimes be a bit of

00:18:52.510 --> 00:18:55.190
an adversive term for people.

00:18:55.190 --> 00:18:59.180
And I'm struck by this idea,

00:18:59.180 --> 00:19:00.700
and the reason I want to explore it is

00:19:00.700 --> 00:19:03.400
because so much of what I see online

00:19:03.400 --> 00:19:06.820
is about generating a lack of balance,

00:19:06.820 --> 00:19:10.740
about being tilted forward at all times,

00:19:10.740 --> 00:19:13.640
really leaning into life
hard, experiencing life,

00:19:13.640 --> 00:19:15.700
you know, living a full life.

00:19:15.700 --> 00:19:18.380
Even the commencement
speech given by Steve Jobs

00:19:18.380 --> 00:19:22.200
on this campus was really
about finding passion, digging.

00:19:22.200 --> 00:19:25.290
You know, that's so much
in the narrative now.

00:19:25.290 --> 00:19:28.530
So maybe you could just
tell us a little bit

00:19:28.530 --> 00:19:31.630
about your experience
with this association,

00:19:31.630 --> 00:19:35.620
if it really exists, between
people's sense of the normalcy,

00:19:35.620 --> 00:19:38.060
or maybe even how boring life can be,

00:19:38.060 --> 00:19:40.713
and their tendency to
become addicts of some sort.

00:19:41.830 --> 00:19:44.595
- Yeah, well, I mean,

00:19:44.595 --> 00:19:49.595
I think that life for
humans has always been hard,

00:19:50.020 --> 00:19:55.020
but I think that now it's
harder in unprecedented ways.

00:19:55.650 --> 00:19:59.370
And I think that the way
that life is really hard now

00:19:59.370 --> 00:20:02.140
is that it actually is really boring.

00:20:02.140 --> 00:20:03.880
And the reason that it's boring is

00:20:03.880 --> 00:20:07.890
because all of our survival
needs are met, right?

00:20:07.890 --> 00:20:10.640
I mean, we don't even
have to leave our homes

00:20:10.640 --> 00:20:13.080
to meet every single physical need,

00:20:13.080 --> 00:20:15.590
you know, as long as
you're of a certain level

00:20:15.590 --> 00:20:19.780
of financial wellbeing,
which frankly, you know,

00:20:19.780 --> 00:20:22.580
we talk so much about,
you know, the income gap,

00:20:22.580 --> 00:20:24.410
and certainly there is this enormous gap

00:20:24.410 --> 00:20:25.530
between rich and poor.

00:20:25.530 --> 00:20:28.320
But that gap is smaller
than it's ever been

00:20:28.320 --> 00:20:30.950
in like the history of humans.

00:20:30.950 --> 00:20:35.710
Even the poorest of the
poor have more excess income

00:20:35.710 --> 00:20:37.000
to spend on leisure goods,

00:20:37.000 --> 00:20:40.170
than they ever have
before in human history.

00:20:40.170 --> 00:20:42.760
If you look at leisure time, for example,

00:20:42.760 --> 00:20:45.770
so people without a high school education

00:20:45.770 --> 00:20:47.920
have 42% more leisure time

00:20:47.920 --> 00:20:51.925
than people with a college degree.

00:20:51.925 --> 00:20:56.925
So my point here is that life is hard now

00:20:58.180 --> 00:21:00.740
in this really weird way,

00:21:00.740 --> 00:21:04.620
in that we don't really have
anything that we have to do.

00:21:04.620 --> 00:21:08.450
So we're all forced to
make stuff up, you know,

00:21:08.450 --> 00:21:13.450
whether it's being a
scientist or being a doctor,

00:21:13.660 --> 00:21:17.100
or being an Olympic athlete, or, you know,

00:21:17.100 --> 00:21:19.480
climbing Mount Everest.

00:21:19.480 --> 00:21:23.830
And people really vary in
their need for friction.

00:21:23.830 --> 00:21:26.360
And some people need a
lot more than others.

00:21:26.360 --> 00:21:29.770
And if they don't have it,
they're really, really unhappy.

00:21:29.770 --> 00:21:32.810
And I do think that a lot
of the people that I see

00:21:32.810 --> 00:21:35.650
with addiction and other
forms of mental illness

00:21:35.650 --> 00:21:38.890
are people who need more friction.

00:21:38.890 --> 00:21:40.970
Like they're unhappy,

00:21:40.970 --> 00:21:43.010
not necessarily because
there's something wrong

00:21:43.010 --> 00:21:43.843
with their brain,

00:21:43.843 --> 00:21:48.070
but because their brain is
not suited to this world.

00:21:48.070 --> 00:21:49.670
- And do you think they have that sense,

00:21:49.670 --> 00:21:51.380
my brain isn't suited to this world,

00:21:51.380 --> 00:21:55.820
or they simply feel a restlessness

00:21:55.820 --> 00:21:58.620
and they're constantly
seeking stimulation?

00:21:58.620 --> 00:22:00.740
- I think that's right, yeah.

00:22:00.740 --> 00:22:04.450
I think it's not really
knowing what's wrong with me,

00:22:04.450 --> 00:22:08.360
and why am I unhappy,
how can I be happier?

00:22:08.360 --> 00:22:09.770
And of course, as you talk about,

00:22:09.770 --> 00:22:12.490
what's so pervasive in our narrative now

00:22:12.490 --> 00:22:16.890
is like find your passion,
you know, find your, you know,

00:22:16.890 --> 00:22:18.520
out of whatever it is, to save the world.

00:22:18.520 --> 00:22:20.400
And in a way that's good

00:22:20.400 --> 00:22:24.440
because it has people out
in the world and seeking.

00:22:24.440 --> 00:22:28.410
But in a way it can also be
misleading in the sense that

00:22:29.270 --> 00:22:31.749
I think people aren't entirely aware

00:22:31.749 --> 00:22:36.370
that the world is a hard
place, and that life is hard,

00:22:36.370 --> 00:22:40.820
and that, you know, like we're
all kind of making it up.

00:22:40.820 --> 00:22:41.888
Do you know what I mean?

00:22:41.888 --> 00:22:42.721
- Yeah.

00:22:42.721 --> 00:22:44.900
Well there's a book by Cal Newport,

00:22:44.900 --> 00:22:45.840
I don't know if you
know Cal Newport's work,

00:22:45.840 --> 00:22:50.040
but you guys are very
symbiotic in your messages.

00:22:50.040 --> 00:22:52.763
He's a professor of computer
science at Georgetown.

00:22:53.660 --> 00:22:54.760
Yes, at Georgetown.

00:22:54.760 --> 00:22:58.130
And wrote a book some years
ago, really ahead of its time,

00:22:58.130 --> 00:22:59.670
called "So Good They Can't Ignore You",

00:22:59.670 --> 00:23:04.670
which is about not
meditating or doing much work

00:23:04.820 --> 00:23:08.410
to try and figure out what
one's passion is by thinking,

00:23:08.410 --> 00:23:10.683
but rather go out and acquire skills,

00:23:10.683 --> 00:23:11.516
- Right.

00:23:11.516 --> 00:23:14.250
- and develop a sense
of passion for something

00:23:14.250 --> 00:23:16.305
by your experience of hard work

00:23:16.305 --> 00:23:18.225
and getting better end feedback.

00:23:18.225 --> 00:23:19.058
- Right.
- A little bit of

00:23:19.058 --> 00:23:19.891
the growth mindset,

00:23:19.891 --> 00:23:21.040
think of our colleague Carol Dweck.

00:23:21.040 --> 00:23:25.080
But he's gone on to
write books, "Deep Work",

00:23:25.080 --> 00:23:27.590
which is all about removing
yourself from technology

00:23:27.590 --> 00:23:28.939
and doing deep work.

00:23:28.939 --> 00:23:29.772
- Yes, right.

00:23:29.772 --> 00:23:31.300
- And he's been a big proponent of

00:23:31.300 --> 00:23:34.475
the evils of context switching
too often throughout the day.

00:23:34.475 --> 00:23:35.308
- [Anna] Yeah.

00:23:35.308 --> 00:23:36.640
- For sake of productivity, mostly.

00:23:36.640 --> 00:23:39.850
His new book is called
"A World Without Email."

00:23:39.850 --> 00:23:41.870
I'm beginning to realize,
as I cite off these books

00:23:41.870 --> 00:23:43.860
and your book, "Dopamine Nation,

00:23:43.860 --> 00:23:46.020
Finding Balance in the Age of Indulgence",

00:23:46.020 --> 00:23:47.520
that maybe the reason why

00:23:47.520 --> 00:23:48.910
you two don't know about one another

00:23:48.910 --> 00:23:50.989
is because neither of
you are on social media.

00:23:50.989 --> 00:23:51.822
- That's it.

00:23:51.822 --> 00:23:52.763
- Right.
- That's it.

00:23:52.763 --> 00:23:54.040
- And yet you're two of
the most productive people

00:23:54.040 --> 00:23:56.710
that I know, including productive authors.

00:23:56.710 --> 00:23:58.180
So that's a discussion unto itself.

00:23:58.180 --> 00:23:59.940
But I find this fascinating.

00:23:59.940 --> 00:24:04.940
So let's talk about the pleasure
pain balance and addiction.

00:24:06.090 --> 00:24:08.030
And I've heard you use this seesaw

00:24:08.030 --> 00:24:09.030
or balance scale,

00:24:09.030 --> 00:24:11.280
- Right.
- analogy before.

00:24:11.280 --> 00:24:15.290
And I think it's a wonderful
one that really, for me,

00:24:15.290 --> 00:24:18.510
clarified what addiction is,

00:24:18.510 --> 00:24:20.593
at least at the mechanistic level.

00:24:21.570 --> 00:24:24.250
- Yeah, so to me, one of the
most significant findings

00:24:24.250 --> 00:24:26.420
in neuroscience in the last 75 years

00:24:26.420 --> 00:24:29.420
is that pleasure and pain are co-located,

00:24:29.420 --> 00:24:31.130
which means the same parts of the brain

00:24:31.130 --> 00:24:34.070
that process pleasure also process pain.

00:24:34.070 --> 00:24:35.910
And they work like a balance.

00:24:35.910 --> 00:24:38.680
So when we feel pleasure,
our balance tips one way,

00:24:38.680 --> 00:24:41.730
when we feel pain, it tips
in the opposite direction.

00:24:41.730 --> 00:24:44.990
And one of the overriding
rules governing this balance

00:24:44.990 --> 00:24:46.560
is that it wants to stay level.

00:24:46.560 --> 00:24:48.380
So it doesn't want to
remain tipped very long

00:24:48.380 --> 00:24:50.000
to pleasure or to pain.

00:24:50.000 --> 00:24:52.470
