I think the latter.

00:36:41.340 --> 00:36:42.470
Then that gets to temperament,

00:36:42.470 --> 00:36:44.073
so I'm going to get that to a second.

00:36:44.073 --> 00:36:46.510
So, in general, what we want is

00:36:46.510 --> 00:36:50.070
some kind of flexibility in that balance,

00:36:50.070 --> 00:36:53.260
and the ability to easily
reassert homeostasis.

00:36:53.260 --> 00:36:55.090
We don't want to break our balance,

00:36:55.090 --> 00:36:57.360
which is possible if we overindulge

00:36:57.360 --> 00:36:58.770
for enough period of time

00:36:58.770 --> 00:37:01.440
and end up with a balance
tipped to the side of pain,

00:37:01.440 --> 00:37:03.920
this dopamine deficit state
we've been talking about.

00:37:03.920 --> 00:37:07.510
We want a flexible,
resilient balance, right,

00:37:07.510 --> 00:37:09.670
which can be sensitive to things going on

00:37:09.670 --> 00:37:10.503
in the environment,

00:37:10.503 --> 00:37:13.430
which can experience
pleasure and approach,

00:37:13.430 --> 00:37:16.360
which can experience
pain and recoil, right?

00:37:16.360 --> 00:37:19.840
This is all adaptive and
healthy and necessary and good.

00:37:19.840 --> 00:37:22.682
We would never want a
balance that doesn't tilt.

00:37:22.682 --> 00:37:23.515
- Right.

00:37:23.515 --> 00:37:25.380
- That would be a disaster,
we wouldn't be human.

00:37:25.380 --> 00:37:28.080
And we wouldn't want that,
it'd be really, really boring.

00:37:28.080 --> 00:37:28.913
On the other hand,

00:37:28.913 --> 00:37:32.350
what people in recovery from
addiction talk about is,

00:37:32.350 --> 00:37:36.070
to some extent having
to learn to live with

00:37:36.070 --> 00:37:39.480
things being a little boring
a lot of the time, right?

00:37:39.480 --> 00:37:42.530
So trying to avoid some of this intensity

00:37:42.530 --> 00:37:46.330
and thrill-seeking and escapism,

00:37:46.330 --> 00:37:49.250
that really is at the core
of addictive tendencies.

00:37:49.250 --> 00:37:51.740
- Sorry to interrupt,
but when you say boring,

00:37:51.740 --> 00:37:53.860
can we add stressful and boring?

00:37:53.860 --> 00:37:54.693
- Yes.

00:37:54.693 --> 00:37:56.863
- Because there are days where I'm not,

00:37:57.840 --> 00:37:59.400
I'm one of these people
that have to remind myself

00:37:59.400 --> 00:38:00.450
to have fun,

00:38:00.450 --> 00:38:01.283
- Yes.
- because I sort of forgot

00:38:01.283 --> 00:38:02.390
what the term means,

00:38:02.390 --> 00:38:04.820
because I like to think that I experience

00:38:04.820 --> 00:38:06.070
a lot of pleasure in little things,

00:38:06.070 --> 00:38:08.030
but I'm a pretty hard-driving guy.

00:38:08.030 --> 00:38:10.520
I like goals and big
milestones and all that stuff.

00:38:10.520 --> 00:38:11.353
Anyway.

00:38:12.490 --> 00:38:16.340
The point being that
many days I'm not bored

00:38:16.340 --> 00:38:18.420
thinking oh, there's nothing to do,

00:38:18.420 --> 00:38:21.480
but I am kind of overwhelmed
by the number of things

00:38:21.480 --> 00:38:23.810
that are really not pleasureful

00:38:23.810 --> 00:38:25.420
that I have to do.
- Yeah, right.

00:38:25.420 --> 00:38:27.708
- I won't mention what they are,

00:38:27.708 --> 00:38:29.560
'cause I don't my colleagues to be like

00:38:29.560 --> 00:38:32.750
that's why you don't respond to emails.

00:38:32.750 --> 00:38:34.670
No, just your email.

00:38:34.670 --> 00:38:36.020
Not yours Anna, but theirs.

00:38:36.920 --> 00:38:38.400
In any event,

00:38:38.400 --> 00:38:41.907
so anxiety and boredom can
hang out together, right?

00:38:41.907 --> 00:38:43.720
Am I correct in?

00:38:43.720 --> 00:38:44.553
- Oh, for sure.

00:38:44.553 --> 00:38:47.610
I mean, actually boredom is
highly anxiety-provoking.

00:38:47.610 --> 00:38:48.544
- Okay.

00:38:48.544 --> 00:38:49.680
That's good to know, 'cause
I think people hear boredom

00:38:49.680 --> 00:38:52.969
and they think like, oh,
there's nothing to do here.

00:38:52.969 --> 00:38:53.802
- [Anna] Right.

00:38:53.802 --> 00:38:54.635
- There's nothing.

00:38:54.635 --> 00:38:55.710
I feel like we have a ton to do,

00:38:55.710 --> 00:38:57.480
we just don't really want to do it.

00:38:57.480 --> 00:38:58.799
- Right, right.

00:38:58.799 --> 00:38:59.787
- As opposed to something
that we're excited to do.

00:38:59.787 --> 00:39:02.410
- Right, okay, so this gets to sort of

00:39:02.410 --> 00:39:03.450
some of the core things.

00:39:03.450 --> 00:39:05.290
Also we were talking about earlier

00:39:05.290 --> 00:39:06.590
about finding your passion.

00:39:06.590 --> 00:39:08.563
So I'm going to try to
link it all together.

00:39:08.563 --> 00:39:11.140
But basically boredom,

00:39:11.140 --> 00:39:14.810
first of all boredom is a rare
experience for modern humans,

00:39:14.810 --> 00:39:17.530
because we're constantly
distracting ourselves

00:39:17.530 --> 00:39:18.520
from the present moment,

00:39:18.520 --> 00:39:22.780
and we have an infinite number
of ways to do that, right.

00:39:22.780 --> 00:39:24.810
But boredom is really, I think,

00:39:24.810 --> 00:39:28.300
an important and necessary experience.

00:39:28.300 --> 00:39:32.480
But it is scary because when
you allow yourself to be bored,

00:39:32.480 --> 00:39:34.250
let's say you were, had
that list of all the things

00:39:34.250 --> 00:39:36.640
you hate to do, but you
actually got them all done.

00:39:36.640 --> 00:39:37.473
Imagine that.

00:39:37.473 --> 00:39:40.370
And you got your forthcoming book done,

00:39:40.370 --> 00:39:42.776
and you did all your interviews.

00:39:42.776 --> 00:39:44.146
- It could happen!

00:39:44.146 --> 00:39:45.167
Lightning could strike.
- Right.

00:39:45.167 --> 00:39:47.780
And you walked your dog,
and you cleaned your house,

00:39:47.780 --> 00:39:49.730
and you went shopping.

00:39:49.730 --> 00:39:51.130
Imagine that for a moment.

00:39:51.130 --> 00:39:53.290
You would be sitting in your house,

00:39:53.290 --> 00:39:58.290
and my guess is you would
be terrified because, wow,

00:39:58.450 --> 00:40:01.090
what am I supposed to do now, right?

00:40:01.090 --> 00:40:03.220
There's nothing I really have to do.

00:40:03.220 --> 00:40:05.190
And that is really, really scary.

00:40:05.190 --> 00:40:06.830
That can feel like free fall.

00:40:06.830 --> 00:40:09.520
And yet that's really an important

00:40:09.520 --> 00:40:11.140
and good experience to have.

00:40:11.140 --> 00:40:12.750
And I think that is an experience

00:40:12.750 --> 00:40:17.750
out of which we can have a
lot of creative initiative,

00:40:18.050 --> 00:40:20.810
but also really consider
our priorities and values.

00:40:20.810 --> 00:40:23.660
Okay, here I am on planet Earth.

00:40:23.660 --> 00:40:25.773
What the he-haw am I
going to do with my life?

00:40:25.773 --> 00:40:27.140
What do I really care about?

00:40:27.140 --> 00:40:28.860
How do I really want to spend my time,

00:40:28.860 --> 00:40:31.440
when I'm not distracting myself, you know,

00:40:31.440 --> 00:40:33.280
in order to spend it.

00:40:33.280 --> 00:40:36.500
And, you know, then this
gets back to our conversation

00:40:36.500 --> 00:40:38.750
a little bit earlier about
finding your passion.

00:40:38.750 --> 00:40:41.790
So I think that one of
the big problems now

00:40:41.790 --> 00:40:43.500
that's very misguided about this idea

00:40:43.500 --> 00:40:45.220
of finding your passion,

00:40:45.220 --> 00:40:48.050
it's almost as if people
are looking to fit the key

00:40:48.050 --> 00:40:51.360
into the lock of the thing
that was meant for them to do.

00:40:51.360 --> 00:40:52.610
- Right, and then
everything will feel like

00:40:52.610 --> 00:40:53.443
a natural progression?

00:40:53.443 --> 00:40:55.220
- Right, and then everything
will be wonderful.

00:40:55.220 --> 00:40:57.570
- I can attest to the fact
that is not how it works

00:40:57.570 --> 00:40:58.810
in any endeavor.
- Yeah, right.

00:40:58.810 --> 00:41:01.163
And that you'll have all
this great success or.

00:41:02.015 --> 00:41:06.310
And here's where I really
think the answer lies.

00:41:06.310 --> 00:41:07.860
And I really, really believe this.

00:41:07.860 --> 00:41:10.826
Stop looking for your passion

00:41:10.826 --> 00:41:15.563
and instead look around
right where you are.

00:41:16.460 --> 00:41:20.290
Stop distracting yourself, look
around right where you are,

00:41:20.290 --> 00:41:23.420
and see what needs to be done.

00:41:23.420 --> 00:41:25.880
So not what do I want to do,

00:41:25.880 --> 00:41:28.830
but what is the work
that needs to be done?

00:41:28.830 --> 00:41:29.663
And more importantly,

00:41:29.663 --> 00:41:32.310
it doesn't have to be some grandiose work.

00:41:32.310 --> 00:41:35.820
Like does the garbage need
to be taken out, right?

00:41:35.820 --> 00:41:38.610
Is there some garbage
on your neighbor's lawn

00:41:38.610 --> 00:41:39.443
that someone threw there,

00:41:39.443 --> 00:41:41.820
that you could actually
bend over and pick up

00:41:41.820 --> 00:41:44.670
and put into the garbage can?

00:41:44.670 --> 00:41:46.540
Look around you.

00:41:46.540 --> 00:41:49.650
There is so much work
that needs to be done

00:41:49.650 --> 00:41:51.670
that nobody wants to do.

00:41:51.670 --> 00:41:55.660
That is really, really important,
and if we all did that,

00:41:55.660 --> 00:41:58.200
I really think the world
would be a much better place.

00:41:58.200 --> 00:42:00.950
And this is what people
who have severe addiction,

00:42:00.950 --> 00:42:02.620
who get into recovery, realize.

00:42:02.620 --> 00:42:06.550
They're like, it's not
about me and my will

00:42:06.550 --> 00:42:09.940
and what I'm going to will
in my life or in the world.

00:42:09.940 --> 00:42:13.250
It's about looking around
what needs to be done.

00:42:13.250 --> 00:42:17.930
What is the work that I am
called to do in this moment?

00:42:17.930 --> 00:42:20.010
Which also is incredibly freeing

00:42:20.010 --> 00:42:22.750
because I don't have to
search for the perfect thing.

00:42:22.750 --> 00:42:25.010
There's a lot of burden
now on young people,

00:42:25.010 --> 00:42:26.810
that they have to find that perfect thing,

00:42:26.810 --> 00:42:28.260
and until they've found
that perfect thing,

00:42:28.260 --> 00:42:29.600
they're going to be miserable.

00:42:29.600 --> 00:42:31.180
You don't have to do that.

00:42:31.180 --> 00:42:32.860
Look at the life you were given,

00:42:32.860 --> 00:42:34.283
look at the people around you,

00:42:34.283 --> 00:42:37.870
look at the jobs that
present themselves to you

00:42:37.870 --> 00:42:42.870
and do that job simply and
honorably, one day at a time,

00:42:43.050 --> 00:42:44.660
with a kind of humility.

00:42:44.660 --> 00:42:47.180
I think this is really
what's so striking to me

00:42:47.180 --> 00:42:49.430
about the wisdom of people in recovery.

00:42:49.430 --> 00:42:51.670
There's this incredible humility

00:42:51.670 --> 00:42:53.350
that comes out of that experience.

00:42:53.350 --> 00:42:56.000
You feel so broken, so ashamed,

00:42:56.000 --> 00:42:58.990
but you pick yourself up one day at a time

00:42:58.990 --> 00:43:02.000
and you build a life that's around

00:43:02.000 --> 00:43:04.680
what can I do right in this moment,

00:43:04.680 --> 00:43:09.360
that might benefit another
person, and thereby benefit me?

00:43:09.360 --> 00:43:14.360
- Yeah it's a really important
point, and if you're willing,

00:43:14.430 --> 00:43:17.950
I'd like to actually stay
on this issue of passion,

00:43:17.950 --> 00:43:22.950
because I think the dopamine systems,

00:43:23.320 --> 00:43:24.923
if I understand them correctly,

00:43:25.890 --> 00:43:29.560
the dopamine systems merge with this work

00:43:29.560 --> 00:43:30.393
that you're referring to,

00:43:30.393 --> 00:43:32.560
this immediacy of things calling to us,

00:43:32.560 --> 00:43:33.830
like taking out the trash,

00:43:33.830 --> 00:43:37.550
which sounds frankly really
boring, to be honest.

00:43:37.550 --> 00:43:40.220
I hate taking out the trash, but I do it,

00:43:40.220 --> 00:43:41.290
'cause I like a clean home

00:43:41.290 --> 00:43:43.323
and I like a home that smells good.

00:43:44.340 --> 00:43:46.630
Or at least doesn't smell bad.

00:43:46.630 --> 00:43:50.220
So we do these things, and
not that we want to offer

00:43:50.220 --> 00:43:54.290
some larger carrot as a
consequence of doing those things.

00:43:54.290 --> 00:43:56.710
But if I understand correctly,
what you're saying is

00:43:56.710 --> 00:44:01.360
in the act of looking at
one's immediate environment,

00:44:01.360 --> 00:44:03.860
acting on that immediate environment,

00:44:03.860 --> 00:44:08.860
we cultivate a relationship
to these circuits in our brain

00:44:09.600 --> 00:44:13.090
about action and reward
that, at least to my mind,

00:44:13.090 --> 00:44:16.670
span the range of small
things being rewarding,

00:44:16.670 --> 00:44:19.060
and then lead us to the
bigger things being rewarding.

00:44:19.060 --> 00:44:21.300
It's not like all we're
going to do is take out trash

00:44:21.300 --> 00:44:22.310
and tend to house.

00:44:22.310 --> 00:44:23.670
We eventually will venture out,

00:44:23.670 --> 00:44:27.490
and we eventually will find
careers and work on those.

00:44:27.490 --> 00:44:28.460
But if I understand correctly,

00:44:28.460 --> 00:44:31.670
you're talking about getting
into a sort of functional

00:44:31.670 --> 00:44:34.090
or adaptive action step,

00:44:34.090 --> 00:44:37.210
and it's the action step that
these days we tend to overlook

00:44:37.210 --> 00:44:39.900
because most of our mindset is in things

00:44:39.900 --> 00:44:43.180
that are truly outside
of our immediate reality.

00:44:43.180 --> 00:44:44.230
Do I have that correct?

00:44:44.230 --> 00:44:45.926
- Yeah, that was beautifully said.

00:44:45.926 --> 00:44:47.480
And I would just add to that,

00:44:47.480 --> 00:44:50.820
I see a lot of young
people who, for example,

00:44:50.820 --> 00:44:53.720
spend most of their waking
hours playing video games,

00:44:53.720 --> 00:44:55.010
and they come to me and they say

00:44:55.010 --> 00:44:57.000
I am anxious and depressed.

00:44:57.000 --> 00:44:58.830
I'm majoring in computer science.

00:44:58.830 --> 00:45:00.683
I hate it, I thought I would like it.

00:45:01.528 --> 00:45:03.040
You know, if I could only find that thing

00:45:03.040 --> 00:45:06.390
that I was really meant to
do, my life would be better.

00:45:06.390 --> 00:45:08.920
And my first intervention for

00:45:08.920 --> 00:45:10.640
the many many people like that

00:45:10.640 --> 00:45:14.280
that I see in clinical care
is, you have it backwards.

00:45:14.280 --> 00:45:16.040
I don't say it quite like that.

00:45:16.040 --> 00:45:17.670
You were waiting for that thing

00:45:17.670 --> 00:45:20.490
to pull you out of the video game world.

00:45:20.490 --> 00:45:22.210
And you're never going to find it,

00:45:22.210 --> 00:45:24.050
as long as you're playing video games.

00:45:24.050 --> 00:45:27.560
'Cause video games are so
powerfully dopaminergic

00:45:27.560 --> 00:45:30.320
that you have this distorted sense of

00:45:30.320 --> 00:45:32.020
really pleasure and pain.

00:45:32.020 --> 00:45:35.370
And you will not be able to
find that thing that you enjoy.

00:45:35.370 --> 00:45:36.940
And so of course the intervention is

00:45:36.940 --> 00:45:40.170
abstain from video games,
reset your reward pathways,

00:45:40.170 --> 00:45:42.190
start with a level balance.

00:45:42.190 --> 00:45:43.610
And what invariably happens,

00:45:43.610 --> 00:45:45.890
and I've just seen it over
20 years so many times

00:45:45.890 --> 00:45:49.163
I've become really a believer in this,

00:45:50.220 --> 00:45:52.040
all of a sudden it's like oh wow,

00:45:52.040 --> 00:45:56.070
my computer science class
is interesting this quarter.

00:45:56.070 --> 00:46:00.780
It's like okay, you know,
you have a receptivity then

00:46:00.780 --> 00:46:03.450
to experiencing pleasure and reward

00:46:03.450 --> 00:46:04.960
in a way you just don't have

00:46:04.960 --> 00:46:07.010
when you're bombarding
your reward pathways

00:46:07.010 --> 00:46:08.910
with these high dopamine drugs.

00:46:08.910 --> 00:46:10.360
- Very interesting.

00:46:10.360 --> 00:46:12.450
And just to underscore this notion

00:46:12.450 --> 00:46:14.320
that tending to the immediate things

00:46:14.320 --> 00:46:16.543
can lead to super performance.

00:46:17.730 --> 00:46:20.260
I may have mentioned it
earlier this episode,

00:46:20.260 --> 00:46:22.300
but if I didn't I'll mention it now,

00:46:22.300 --> 00:46:24.240
which is I have the great privilege

00:46:24.240 --> 00:46:26.210
of having some close friends
that were in the SEAL teams

00:46:26.210 --> 00:46:27.677
and doing some work
with those communities.

00:46:27.677 --> 00:46:30.530
And it's a remarkable community
for reasons that I think

00:46:30.530 --> 00:46:31.840
most people don't understand.

00:46:31.840 --> 00:46:33.300
People think, they see the images,

00:46:33.300 --> 00:46:34.940
carrying logs down the
beach, and all this,

00:46:34.940 --> 00:46:37.130
blowing stuff up, all the stuff that's fun

00:46:37.130 --> 00:46:38.250
for guys like that.

00:46:38.250 --> 00:46:42.310
But all of the guys I know
who were in the SEAL teams

00:46:42.310 --> 00:46:46.190
have this sense of duty
about immediate things,

00:46:46.190 --> 00:46:47.960
and not just holding the door and doing,

00:46:47.960 --> 00:46:49.740
helping with the dishes
and moving things around.

00:46:49.740 --> 00:46:52.220
They are constantly
scanning their environment

00:46:52.220 --> 00:46:53.477
for what can be done.

00:46:53.477 --> 00:46:54.310
- Ah!

00:46:54.310 --> 00:46:57.010
- They essentially conquer
every environment they're in.

00:46:57.010 --> 00:47:00.830
They are also some of the
most competitive human beings

00:47:00.830 --> 00:47:02.220
in the world, and they do it,

00:47:02.220 --> 00:47:04.710
unless they're in the act of war fighting,

00:47:04.710 --> 00:47:06.423
which is their real job.

00:47:07.400 --> 00:47:10.470
They do it in every environment,
in a very benevolent way.

00:47:10.470 --> 00:47:13.030
And it's a remarkable thing because it,

00:47:13.030 --> 00:47:16.380
I think it's what is part of
what they're selected for.

00:47:16.380 --> 00:47:18.740
And, you know, there's a range there.

00:47:18.740 --> 00:47:20.490
But I think when we hear about

00:47:20.490 --> 00:47:22.540
tending to the immediate things,

00:47:22.540 --> 00:47:24.110
or this phrase, you know,

00:47:24.110 --> 00:47:25.760
how you do one thing
