'cause that totally resonates for me,

00:47:59.150 --> 00:48:01.020
and is very consistent with people

00:48:01.020 --> 00:48:02.520
in recovery from addiction

00:48:02.520 --> 00:48:04.920
who learn to take it one day at a time,

00:48:04.920 --> 00:48:06.390
which is one of the, you know,

00:48:06.390 --> 00:48:09.030
standard lingo from Alcoholics Anonymous

00:48:09.030 --> 00:48:10.380
and other 12-step groups.

00:48:10.380 --> 00:48:12.600
But I think also, as you say, you know,

00:48:12.600 --> 00:48:16.490
our brain is really wired
for the 24-hour period.

00:48:16.490 --> 00:48:21.000
We're not very good at sort
of the, you know, 10 year, 20.

00:48:21.000 --> 00:48:22.540
I mean we have this huge frontal lobes

00:48:22.540 --> 00:48:24.530
and yes, we're great planners and we can,

00:48:24.530 --> 00:48:27.710
but if we live too much in that space,

00:48:27.710 --> 00:48:30.590
we can really get very anxious
and depressed and lost,

00:48:30.590 --> 00:48:33.280
and either catastrophize or get grandiose.

00:48:33.280 --> 00:48:36.155
But if you can chunk it down to a day,

00:48:36.155 --> 00:48:38.690
what people in recovery talk about is how,

00:48:38.690 --> 00:48:41.410
if I can just do today right,

00:48:41.410 --> 00:48:44.470
then I will get a chain of days

00:48:44.470 --> 00:48:49.000
that seem insignificant
in their individual units,

00:48:49.000 --> 00:48:51.820
but after six months
or a year or two years

00:48:51.820 --> 00:48:55.940
of those good days, I've got
two very good years, right,

00:48:55.940 --> 00:48:57.610
and I look back and it's like oh wow,

00:48:57.610 --> 00:48:59.640
I guess I did all that.

00:48:59.640 --> 00:49:01.990
But I think that's really,
you know, one of the keys,

00:49:01.990 --> 00:49:03.990
is really taking it one day at a time,

00:49:03.990 --> 00:49:04.830
which your SEALs,

00:49:04.830 --> 00:49:07.480
and also this connecting
with the environment, right?

00:49:07.480 --> 00:49:10.450
So being awake and alert
to your environment,

00:49:10.450 --> 00:49:12.320
and connecting with your environment,

00:49:12.320 --> 00:49:13.740
not trying to escape it.

00:49:13.740 --> 00:49:16.640
And of course escapism is
what we all want and desire,

00:49:16.640 --> 00:49:18.550
that experience of non being.

00:49:18.550 --> 00:49:20.950
And we get it from the
internet or from drugs

00:49:20.950 --> 00:49:23.980
or whatever it is, but
it's the booby prize.

00:49:23.980 --> 00:49:27.520
Because ultimately it takes
you further and further away

00:49:27.520 --> 00:49:29.385
from your immediate environment,

00:49:29.385 --> 00:49:30.820
which is where we really have to connect

00:49:30.820 --> 00:49:33.560
to get that sense of
grounded-ness and authenticity,

00:49:33.560 --> 00:49:36.620
and like of being in our own lives.

00:49:36.620 --> 00:49:37.970
- Well I think the unit of the day

00:49:37.970 --> 00:49:40.507
is something that comes
up again and again,

00:49:40.507 --> 00:49:42.900
in my discussions with colleagues

00:49:42.900 --> 00:49:45.240
who are extremely successful,

00:49:45.240 --> 00:49:47.195
and who also have balanced lives.

00:49:47.195 --> 00:49:48.028
- Right.

00:49:48.028 --> 00:49:49.260
- This actually came up in the discussion

00:49:49.260 --> 00:49:53.950
with Karl Deisseroth, who is
also a successful scientist

00:49:53.950 --> 00:49:56.950
and clinician and, you know,
manages a family, et cetera.

00:49:56.950 --> 00:49:59.860
So the unit of the day,
I think, is fundamental.

00:49:59.860 --> 00:50:02.330
And those stack up, as you mentioned.

00:50:02.330 --> 00:50:04.320
So along those lines,

00:50:04.320 --> 00:50:06.740
I've heard you say that in order to reset

00:50:06.740 --> 00:50:08.520
the dopamine system,

00:50:08.520 --> 00:50:12.270
essentially in order to
break an addictive pattern,

00:50:12.270 --> 00:50:13.483
to become un-addicted,

00:50:15.160 --> 00:50:19.700
30 days of zero interaction
with that substance,

00:50:19.700 --> 00:50:21.450
that person, et cetera.

00:50:21.450 --> 00:50:22.680
- Right.
- Is that correct?

00:50:22.680 --> 00:50:25.960
- Yeah, and 30 days is,
in my clinical experience,

00:50:25.960 --> 00:50:27.750
the average amount of time it takes

00:50:27.750 --> 00:50:29.880
for the brain to reset reward pathways

00:50:29.880 --> 00:50:32.810
for dopamine transmission
to regenerate itself.

00:50:32.810 --> 00:50:34.770
There's also a little bit of science

00:50:34.770 --> 00:50:36.820
that suggests that that's true.

00:50:36.820 --> 00:50:39.000
Some imaging studies showing that

00:50:39.000 --> 00:50:41.480
our brains are still in
a dopamine-deficit state

00:50:41.480 --> 00:50:44.880
two weeks after we've been using our drug.

00:50:44.880 --> 00:50:47.620
And then a study by Schukit and Brown

00:50:47.620 --> 00:50:51.190
which took a group of depressed men

00:50:51.190 --> 00:50:53.710
who also were addicted to alcohol,

00:50:53.710 --> 00:50:56.880
put them in a hospital where they,

00:50:56.880 --> 00:50:58.480
they received no treatment for depression

00:50:58.480 --> 00:51:01.430
but they had no access
to alcohol in that time.

00:51:01.430 --> 00:51:02.550
And after four weeks,

00:51:02.550 --> 00:51:06.460
80% of them no longer met
criteria for major depression.

00:51:06.460 --> 00:51:10.040
So again, this idea that
by depriving ourselves

00:51:10.040 --> 00:51:14.540
of this high dopamine high
reward substance or behavior,

00:51:14.540 --> 00:51:17.160
we allow our brains to
regenerate its own dopamine,

00:51:17.160 --> 00:51:18.770
for the balance to really equilibrate.

00:51:18.770 --> 00:51:19.970
And then we're in a place

00:51:19.970 --> 00:51:22.670
where we can sort of enjoy other things.

00:51:22.670 --> 00:51:24.220
- So that progressive narrowing

00:51:24.220 --> 00:51:26.320
- Right.
- of what brings one pleasure,

00:51:26.320 --> 00:51:27.440
eventually expands.

00:51:27.440 --> 00:51:30.170
So I'd like to dissect out that 30 days

00:51:30.170 --> 00:51:31.563
a little more finely.

00:51:32.430 --> 00:51:35.430
And I also want to address

00:51:35.430 --> 00:51:38.520
how does one stop doing
something for 30 days,

00:51:38.520 --> 00:51:40.720
if the thing is a thought?

00:51:40.720 --> 00:51:43.930
So we'll kind of, I'll put that
on the shelf for the moment.

00:51:43.930 --> 00:51:45.743
So days one through 10,

00:51:47.200 --> 00:51:49.669
I would imagine will
be very uncomfortable.

00:51:49.669 --> 00:51:50.502
- [Anna] Yes.

00:51:50.502 --> 00:51:52.870
- They're going to suck
basically, to be quite honest,

00:51:52.870 --> 00:51:56.963
because the way you described
this pleasure pain balance,

00:51:56.963 --> 00:52:00.270
to my mind says that if you remove

00:52:00.270 --> 00:52:03.110
what little pleasure one is
getting, or a lot of pleasure

00:52:03.110 --> 00:52:06.280
from engaging in some
behavior, that's gone.

00:52:06.280 --> 00:52:08.860
The pain system is really ramped up.

00:52:08.860 --> 00:52:11.720
And nothing is making me feel good.

00:52:11.720 --> 00:52:13.260
I'll just use myself as an example.

00:52:13.260 --> 00:52:16.700
I'm not in recovery but, you know,

00:52:16.700 --> 00:52:19.270
that 10 days is going to be miserable.

00:52:19.270 --> 00:52:23.660
Anxiety, trouble sleeping,
physical agitation.

00:52:23.660 --> 00:52:25.300
- Yes.
- To the point where,

00:52:25.300 --> 00:52:28.410
you know, maybe impulsive, angry.

00:52:28.410 --> 00:52:30.860
Should one expect all of that?

00:52:30.860 --> 00:52:34.110
Should the family members of
people expect all of that?

00:52:34.110 --> 00:52:34.943
- Yeah.

00:52:34.943 --> 00:52:36.270
So what I say to patients,

00:52:36.270 --> 00:52:39.190
and it's a really important
piece of this intervention,

00:52:39.190 --> 00:52:42.920
is that you will feel worse
before you feel better.

00:52:42.920 --> 00:52:43.790
- For how long,

00:52:43.790 --> 00:52:45.380
is probably the first question they ask,

00:52:45.380 --> 00:52:46.213
right?
- Yes.

00:52:46.213 --> 00:52:49.110
And I say usually, in
my clinical experience,

00:52:49.110 --> 00:52:50.850
you'll feel worse for two weeks,

00:52:50.850 --> 00:52:53.630
but if you can make it
through those first two weeks,

00:52:53.630 --> 00:52:56.270
the sun will start to
come out in week three.

00:52:56.270 --> 00:52:57.640
And by week four,

00:52:57.640 --> 00:53:00.860
most people are feeling a
whole lot better than they were

00:53:00.860 --> 00:53:03.746
before they stopped using their substance.

00:53:03.746 --> 00:53:07.190
So yeah, you have to, it's a hard thing.

00:53:07.190 --> 00:53:09.150
Like you have to sign up for it.

00:53:09.150 --> 00:53:11.880
And I will say, obviously there
are people with addictions

00:53:11.880 --> 00:53:14.990
that are so severe that as
long as they have access

00:53:14.990 --> 00:53:16.100
to their drug or behavior,

00:53:16.100 --> 00:53:17.780
they're not able to stop themselves.

00:53:17.780 --> 00:53:18.910
And that's why we have, you know,

00:53:18.910 --> 00:53:20.366
higher levels of care,

00:53:20.366 --> 00:53:21.240
- Sure.

00:53:21.240 --> 00:53:22.073
- residential treatment.

00:53:22.073 --> 00:53:24.160
So this is not going to be for
everybody, this intervention,

00:53:24.160 --> 00:53:26.530
but it's amazing how many people

00:53:26.530 --> 00:53:29.310
with really severe addictions
to things like heroin,

00:53:29.310 --> 00:53:34.000
cocaine, you know, very
severe pornography addictions.

00:53:34.000 --> 00:53:36.790
I posit this, I do it as an experiment.

00:53:36.790 --> 00:53:39.520
I said you know what,
let's try this experiment.

00:53:39.520 --> 00:53:42.450
I'm always amazed, number one,
how many of them are willing.

00:53:42.450 --> 00:53:45.060
And number two, how many of
them are actually able to do it.

00:53:45.060 --> 00:53:46.860
They are able to do it.

00:53:46.860 --> 00:53:50.090
And so that little nudge is
sort of just what they need,

00:53:50.090 --> 00:53:53.210
And the carrot is, you know,

00:53:53.210 --> 00:53:54.930
there's a better life out there for you

00:53:54.930 --> 00:53:58.100
and you'll be able to taste it in a month.

00:53:58.100 --> 00:54:00.900
You really will be able to begin to see

00:54:00.900 --> 00:54:04.230
that you can feel better,
and that there's another way.

00:54:04.230 --> 00:54:09.230
- So the way you describe
it seems like it's hard,

00:54:09.630 --> 00:54:11.410
but it's doable for most people,

00:54:11.410 --> 00:54:12.840
not everybody.
- Yeah, right.

00:54:12.840 --> 00:54:15.950
- And we'll return to
that category of people

00:54:15.950 --> 00:54:17.633
who can't do that on their own.

00:54:19.400 --> 00:54:24.400
Well, then days 21 through
30, people are feeling better.

00:54:25.380 --> 00:54:27.505
The sun is starting to
come out, as you mentioned,

00:54:27.505 --> 00:54:30.460
which translates in the
narrative we've created here,

00:54:30.460 --> 00:54:32.440
and supported by biology,

00:54:32.440 --> 00:54:34.870
that dopamine is starting to be released

00:54:34.870 --> 00:54:38.130
in response to the taste of
a really good cup of coffee,

00:54:38.130 --> 00:54:39.620
- Yes, exactly.
- for instance.

00:54:39.620 --> 00:54:43.600
Whereas before it was
only to insert, you know,

00:54:43.600 --> 00:54:44.433
addictive behavior.

00:54:44.433 --> 00:54:46.420
- Right, that's right.
- Whichever it happens to be.

00:54:46.420 --> 00:54:47.270
- Of course, coffee can be addictive too,

00:54:47.270 --> 00:54:48.103
but we'll leave that

00:54:48.103 --> 00:54:49.367
aside.
- Sure, yeah.

00:54:49.367 --> 00:54:51.460
I feel like coffee has a kind of

00:54:51.460 --> 00:54:54.170
consumption limiting mechanism built-in,

00:54:54.170 --> 00:54:57.600
where at some point you
just can't ingest anymore.

00:54:57.600 --> 00:54:59.430
- Yeah.
- But maybe that's wrong.

00:54:59.430 --> 00:55:03.690
Sorry to give lift to the
caffeine addicts out there.

00:55:03.690 --> 00:55:07.113
As I clutch my mug.

00:55:08.270 --> 00:55:11.060
So days 21 through 30.

00:55:11.060 --> 00:55:14.440
I've seen a lot of people
go through addiction

00:55:14.440 --> 00:55:15.273
and addiction treatment.

00:55:15.273 --> 00:55:18.400
I've spent a lot of time
in those places, actually,

00:55:18.400 --> 00:55:19.620
looking at it, researching.

00:55:19.620 --> 00:55:21.010
I've got friends in that community.

00:55:21.010 --> 00:55:22.743
I'm close with that community.

00:55:23.630 --> 00:55:26.070
One thing I've seen over and over again,

00:55:26.070 --> 00:55:28.380
sadly often in the same individuals,

00:55:28.380 --> 00:55:33.380
is they get sober from
whatever, they're doing great.

00:55:35.090 --> 00:55:36.610
These are people with families.

00:55:36.610 --> 00:55:38.000
These are people that you

00:55:38.000 --> 00:55:40.350
discard your normal image of an addict

00:55:40.350 --> 00:55:44.160
and insert the most normal, typical,

00:55:44.160 --> 00:55:46.180
whatever, healthy person you can imagine.

00:55:46.180 --> 00:55:49.970
'Cause a lot of these people
you wouldn't know were addicts.

00:55:49.970 --> 00:55:52.920
And then all of a sudden
you get this call,

00:55:52.920 --> 00:55:55.850
so-and-so's back in jail.

00:55:55.850 --> 00:55:57.880
So-and-so's wife is going to leave him

00:55:57.880 --> 00:56:01.120
because he drank two bottles of wine

00:56:01.120 --> 00:56:03.750
and took a Xanax at 7:00 a.m.,

00:56:03.750 --> 00:56:06.260
crashed his truck into a pole,
has got two beautiful kids.

00:56:06.260 --> 00:56:09.640
Like how did this happen again?

00:56:09.640 --> 00:56:12.220
To the point where by the
fourth and fifth time,

00:56:12.220 --> 00:56:14.720
people are just done.

00:56:14.720 --> 00:56:16.010
I mean maybe people,

00:56:16.010 --> 00:56:17.860
you might be able to detect
the frustration in my voice.

00:56:17.860 --> 00:56:20.130
I'm dealing with this,
with somebody that's like,

00:56:20.130 --> 00:56:22.810
I don't even know that I
want to help this time.

00:56:22.810 --> 00:56:25.200
It's been so many times,

00:56:25.200 --> 00:56:27.570
to the point where I'm starting to wonder

00:56:27.570 --> 00:56:29.550
is this person just an addict.

00:56:29.550 --> 00:56:33.080
This is just kind of what
they do and who they are.

00:56:33.080 --> 00:56:35.130
And you never want to
give up on people but,

00:56:35.130 --> 00:56:37.040
and I'm hanging in there for them.

00:56:37.040 --> 00:56:41.790
But I will say that many
people have given up on them.

00:56:41.790 --> 00:56:44.160
And so what I'd like to
talk about in this context

00:56:44.160 --> 00:56:48.355
is what sorts of things help other people

00:56:48.355 --> 00:56:49.360
that we know that are addicted?

00:56:49.360 --> 00:56:51.560
What really helps?

00:56:51.560 --> 00:56:56.070
Not what could help,
but what really helps.

00:56:56.070 --> 00:57:01.070
And are there certain people
for whom it's hopeless?

00:57:01.530 --> 00:57:03.620
I mean, I don't like to hold
the conversation that way,

00:57:03.620 --> 00:57:05.971
but I wouldn't be close
to the real life data

00:57:05.971 --> 00:57:07.870
if I didn't ask.

00:57:07.870 --> 00:57:09.890
Is it hopeless, are there people who just

00:57:09.890 --> 00:57:14.160
will not be able to
quit their substance use

00:57:14.160 --> 00:57:17.840
or their addictive behavior,
despite, I have to assume,

00:57:17.840 --> 00:57:18.933
really wanting to?

00:57:20.200 --> 00:57:23.700
- Yeah, so there are people who will die

00:57:23.700 --> 00:57:25.550
of their disease of addiction, you know,

00:57:25.550 --> 00:57:27.850
and I think conceptualizing
it as a disease

00:57:27.850 --> 00:57:29.530
is a helpful frame.

00:57:29.530 --> 00:57:32.940
There are other frames that
we could use, but I do think,

00:57:32.940 --> 00:57:37.130
given the brain physiologic
changes that occur

00:57:37.130 --> 00:57:40.400
with sustained heavy drug use,

00:57:40.400 --> 00:57:42.850
and what we know happens to the brain,

00:57:42.850 --> 00:57:47.560
it is really reasonable to
think of it as a brain disease.

00:57:47.560 --> 00:57:51.610
And for me, the real window of,

00:57:51.610 --> 00:57:54.810
let's say being able
to access my compassion

00:57:54.810 --> 00:57:57.740
around people who are repeat relapsers,

00:57:57.740 --> 00:57:59.760
even when their life is so much better

00:57:59.760 --> 00:58:00.593
when they're in recovery.
- Oh yeah, yeah.

00:58:00.593 --> 00:58:02.373
- It's like a no-brainer, right?

00:58:03.540 --> 00:58:05.480
Is to conceptualize this balance

00:58:05.480 --> 00:58:06.870
and the dopamine deficit state,

00:58:06.870 --> 00:58:09.890
and a balance tilted to the side of pain.

00:58:09.890 --> 00:58:13.170
And to imagine that for some people,

00:58:13.170 --> 00:58:16.980
after a month or six months,
or maybe even six years,

00:58:16.980 --> 00:58:20.170
their balance is still
tipped to the side of pain.

00:58:20.170 --> 00:58:24.180
That on some level that
balance has lost its resilience

00:58:24.180 --> 00:58:26.680
and its ability to restore homeostasis.

00:58:26.680 --> 00:58:28.250
- It's almost like the
hinge on that balance

00:58:28.250 --> 00:58:29.124
- Yes.
- is messed up.

00:58:29.124 --> 00:58:30.140
- Exactly.

00:58:30.140 --> 00:58:31.900
And so, I mean,

00:58:31.900 --> 00:58:33.980
for someone who's never
experienced addiction,

00:58:33.980 --> 00:58:37.520
like yourself, maybe one
way to conceptualize it is.

00:58:37.520 --> 00:58:38.353
- Well I didn't say that.

00:58:38.353 --> 00:58:39.186
- [Anna] Oh okay.

00:58:40.610 --> 00:58:43.920
- To be clear, I was not
referring to myself, but I,

00:58:43.920 --> 00:58:47.670
in this example I was giving,
if I were, I would come clean.

00:58:47.670 --> 00:58:49.810
I would reveal that.

00:58:49.810 --> 00:58:51.040
But I think that,

00:58:51.040 --> 00:58:53.840
especially after hearing
some of your lectures

00:58:53.840 --> 00:58:56.500
and descriptions of the range
of things that are addictive,

00:58:56.500 --> 00:58:59.680
I think I've been fortunate
I don't have a propensity

00:58:59.680 --> 00:59:00.720
for drugs or alcohol.

00:59:00.720 --> 00:59:01.553
- Right, okay.

00:59:01.553 --> 00:59:03.760
- I'm lucky in that way.
- Right, right.

00:59:03.760 --> 00:59:05.850
- Frankly, if they remove all
the alcohol from the planet,

00:59:05.850 --> 00:59:06.760
I'll just be relieved

00:59:06.760 --> 00:59:07.950
because no one will
offer it to me any more.

00:59:07.950 --> 00:59:08.783
- [Anna] Right, right.

00:59:08.783 --> 00:59:11.140
- So don't send me any alcohol.

00:59:11.140 --> 00:59:12.130
It won't go to me.

00:59:12.130 --> 00:59:13.574
- [Anna] Right.

00:59:13.574 --> 00:59:16.413
- But I don't have that,

00:59:17.600 --> 00:59:20.330
I like to think I have the compassion,

00:59:20.330 --> 00:59:25.330
but I don't that empathy for, you know,

00:59:27.390 --> 00:59:29.660
taking a really good situation,

00:59:29.660 --> 00:59:31.927
and what from the outside looks to be

00:59:31.927 --> 00:59:33.760
- Right, right.
