00:59:47.874 --> 00:59:49.573
and so you've got the
severe end of things.

00:59:50.840 --> 00:59:55.000
Imagine that you had an itch
somewhere on your body, okay.

00:59:55.000 --> 00:59:57.160
And it was, I mean, we've
all had that, like, you know,

00:59:57.160 --> 01:00:00.030
whatever the source, it
was super, super itchy.

01:00:00.030 --> 01:00:03.940
You can go for, you know,
if you really focus,

01:00:03.940 --> 01:00:06.890
you could go for a pretty
good amount of time

01:00:06.890 --> 01:00:08.320
not scratching it,

01:00:08.320 --> 01:00:12.690
but the moment you stopped
focusing on not scratching it,

01:00:12.690 --> 01:00:13.523
you would scratch it.

01:00:13.523 --> 01:00:16.600
And maybe you'd do it while
you were asleep, right.

01:00:16.600 --> 01:00:21.600
And that is what happens to
people with severe addiction.

01:00:21.880 --> 01:00:24.310
That balance is essentially broken.

01:00:24.310 --> 01:00:26.410
Homeostasis does not get restored,

01:00:26.410 --> 01:00:28.960
despite sustained abstinence.

01:00:28.960 --> 01:00:33.400
They're living with that
constant specter of that pull.

01:00:33.400 --> 01:00:35.130
It never goes away.

01:00:35.130 --> 01:00:36.810
So let me say, there are
lots of people with addiction

01:00:36.810 --> 01:00:37.970
for whom that does go away.

01:00:37.970 --> 01:00:40.310
And it goes away at four
weeks for many of them.

01:00:40.310 --> 01:00:45.310
But in severe cases, that's
always there and it's lingering,

01:00:45.360 --> 01:00:49.120
and it's the moment when they're
not focusing on not using,

01:00:49.120 --> 01:00:50.200
it's like a reflex.

01:00:50.200 --> 01:00:51.920
They fall back into it.

01:00:51.920 --> 01:00:53.200
It's not purposeful.

01:00:53.200 --> 01:00:55.240
It's not because they want to get high.

01:00:55.240 --> 01:00:57.050
It's not because they value using drugs

01:00:57.050 --> 01:00:58.650
more than they do their family.

01:00:58.650 --> 01:00:59.483
None of that.

01:00:59.483 --> 01:01:04.483
It's that really they cannot not do it

01:01:04.530 --> 01:01:06.610
when given the opportunity,

01:01:06.610 --> 01:01:08.940
and that moment when they're
not thinking about it.

01:01:08.940 --> 01:01:09.880
Does that make sense?

01:01:09.880 --> 01:01:10.840
- That's a great description

01:01:10.840 --> 01:01:12.480
and actually in that description

01:01:12.480 --> 01:01:15.160
I can feel a bit of empathy,

01:01:15.160 --> 01:01:16.930
because the way you described

01:01:16.930 --> 01:01:18.380
scratching an itch in your sleep.

01:01:18.380 --> 01:01:19.790
- Yeah.
- You know,

01:01:19.790 --> 01:01:21.525
I've done that with mosquito
bites and some of them,

01:01:21.525 --> 01:01:22.866
- Right.
- you're scratching, you know,

01:01:22.866 --> 01:01:26.330
like you wake up scratching
that mosquito bite.

01:01:26.330 --> 01:01:31.330
And I also have to admit
that I've experienced

01:01:31.360 --> 01:01:33.610
not feeling like I want
to pick up my phone

01:01:33.610 --> 01:01:36.800
because it's so rewarding, but
just finding myself doing it.

01:01:36.800 --> 01:01:37.690
- Yes, of course,

01:01:37.690 --> 01:01:38.523
yes.
- Like I'm not going to

01:01:38.523 --> 01:01:39.767
use this thing, I'm not
going to use this thing,

01:01:39.767 --> 01:01:41.650
and then just finding myself doing it,

01:01:41.650 --> 01:01:43.090
like what am I doing here?
- Yes, right, right.

01:01:43.090 --> 01:01:44.760
- Sort of the how did I get back

01:01:44.760 --> 01:01:46.487
here again?
- Yes, right.

01:01:46.487 --> 01:01:49.440
- And I know enough about
brain function to understand

01:01:49.440 --> 01:01:53.510
that we have circuits that
generate deliberate behavior.

01:01:53.510 --> 01:01:55.530
And we have circuits that
generate reflexive behavior.

01:01:55.530 --> 01:01:58.370
And one of the goals of the nervous system

01:01:58.370 --> 01:02:01.120
is to make the deliberate stuff reflexive,

01:02:01.120 --> 01:02:02.420
so you don't have to make the decision,

01:02:02.420 --> 01:02:05.940
because decision-making is
a very costly thing to do.

01:02:05.940 --> 01:02:06.773
- Exactly.

01:02:06.773 --> 01:02:07.606
- Decision-making of any kind.

01:02:07.606 --> 01:02:08.439
- [Anna] Right, right.

01:02:08.439 --> 01:02:09.803
- So that does really help.

01:02:13.680 --> 01:02:18.290
I want to just try and weave
together this dopamine puzzle,

01:02:18.290 --> 01:02:20.690
however, because if by week,

01:02:20.690 --> 01:02:25.690
so first phase of this 30 or 40 day detox,

01:02:25.866 --> 01:02:27.067
it's like a dopamine fast,

01:02:27.067 --> 01:02:29.370
- Right.
- right, okay.

01:02:29.370 --> 01:02:30.510
First 10 days are miserable.

01:02:30.510 --> 01:02:33.030
Middle 10 days, the clouds are out,

01:02:33.030 --> 01:02:35.110
there may be some shards
of sunlight coming through.

01:02:35.110 --> 01:02:38.070
And then all of a sudden
sun starts to come out,

01:02:38.070 --> 01:02:39.790
it gets brighter and brighter.

01:02:39.790 --> 01:02:42.670
Why is it then that people will relapse,

01:02:42.670 --> 01:02:44.960
not just after getting fired from a job

01:02:44.960 --> 01:02:45.920
or their spouse leaving them,

01:02:45.920 --> 01:02:47.633
but when things are going really well?

01:02:47.633 --> 01:02:49.030
- Yes.
- Is it this

01:02:49.030 --> 01:02:50.710
unconscious mechanism?

01:02:50.710 --> 01:02:52.980
'Cause I've seen this before.

01:02:52.980 --> 01:02:53.990
They have a great win,

01:02:53.990 --> 01:02:57.700
I have a friend who's a
really impressive creative.

01:02:57.700 --> 01:03:00.430
I don't want to reveal any more than that.

01:03:00.430 --> 01:03:03.400
And relapsed upon getting another

01:03:03.400 --> 01:03:07.700
really terrific opportunity to
create for the entire world.

01:03:07.700 --> 01:03:09.210
And I was like how can that happen?

01:03:09.210 --> 01:03:10.480
But now I'm beginning to wonder,

01:03:10.480 --> 01:03:13.210
was it the dopamine
associated with that win

01:03:13.210 --> 01:03:16.103
that opened the spigot
on his dopamine system?

01:03:17.010 --> 01:03:19.860
Because it happened in a phase of

01:03:19.860 --> 01:03:22.280
a really great stretch of life.

01:03:22.280 --> 01:03:23.890
- Yeah, right.

01:03:23.890 --> 01:03:27.690
Yeah, so you raise that great
point about triggers, right?

01:03:27.690 --> 01:03:30.480
And triggers are things that make us

01:03:30.480 --> 01:03:33.050
want to go back to using our drug.

01:03:33.050 --> 01:03:35.340
And the key thing about
triggers, whatever they are,

01:03:35.340 --> 01:03:39.070
is they also release a little
bit of dopamine, right?

01:03:39.070 --> 01:03:43.310
So just thinking about
whatever the trigger is

01:03:43.310 --> 01:03:45.250
that we associate with drug use,

01:03:45.250 --> 01:03:47.240
or just thinking about drug use,

01:03:47.240 --> 01:03:50.040
can already release this
anticipatory dopamine,

01:03:50.040 --> 01:03:51.220
this new little mini spike.

01:03:51.220 --> 01:03:53.710
But here's the part that I
think is really fascinating.

01:03:53.710 --> 01:03:57.240
That mini spike is followed
by a mini deficit state.

01:03:57.240 --> 01:03:59.810
So it goes up and then it
doesn't go back down to baseline,

01:03:59.810 --> 01:04:02.670
it goes below baseline tonic levels.

01:04:02.670 --> 01:04:04.470
And that's craving, right?

01:04:04.470 --> 01:04:09.470
So that anticipation is
immediately followed by

01:04:09.820 --> 01:04:11.180
wanting the drug.

01:04:11.180 --> 01:04:12.900
And it's that dopamine deficit state

01:04:12.900 --> 01:04:16.810
that drives the motivation
to go and get the drug.

01:04:16.810 --> 01:04:17.890
So many people talk about dopamine

01:04:17.890 --> 01:04:19.610
as not really about pleasure,

01:04:19.610 --> 01:04:22.460
but about wanting and about motivation.

01:04:22.460 --> 01:04:24.460
And so it is that deficit state

01:04:24.460 --> 01:04:27.207
that then drives the locomotion to get it.

01:04:27.207 --> 01:04:29.200
- And earlier your description of dopamine

01:04:29.200 --> 01:04:30.853
being involved in the desire for more,

01:04:30.853 --> 01:04:33.570
giving the sense of
reward, but also movement.

01:04:33.570 --> 01:04:34.770
- Right.
- I have to assume

01:04:34.770 --> 01:04:36.195
that those things are braided together

01:04:36.195 --> 01:04:37.430
- Yes, yes.
- in our nervous system,

01:04:37.430 --> 01:04:41.050
for the specific intention of
when you feel something good,

01:04:41.050 --> 01:04:42.350
then you feel the pain.

01:04:42.350 --> 01:04:43.183
- Yes.
- But maybe

01:04:43.183 --> 01:04:44.016
you don't notice it.

01:04:44.016 --> 01:04:44.849
And then the next thing you know,

01:04:44.849 --> 01:04:46.073
you're pursuing more of the thing that-

01:04:46.073 --> 01:04:48.350
- And I love the way you use
the word braided together,

01:04:48.350 --> 01:04:49.183
that's beautiful.

01:04:49.183 --> 01:04:50.530
And let me also just say,

01:04:50.530 --> 01:04:52.900
something that I find also fascinating

01:04:52.900 --> 01:04:55.660
in my work with patients,
and I see this all the time.

01:04:55.660 --> 01:04:59.940
There are people for whom
bad life experiences, loss,

01:04:59.940 --> 01:05:03.580
you know, in any form, stress,
in many different forms,

01:05:03.580 --> 01:05:06.380
that's a trigger, but
there are absolutely people

01:05:06.380 --> 01:05:09.970
for whom the trigger is things going well.

01:05:09.970 --> 01:05:12.380
And the things going well can be like

01:05:12.380 --> 01:05:13.610
the reward of the things going well,

01:05:13.610 --> 01:05:16.740
but very often what it
is is the removal of

01:05:16.740 --> 01:05:18.640
the hypervigilant state

01:05:18.640 --> 01:05:21.430
that's required to keep
their use in check.

01:05:21.430 --> 01:05:24.650
So it's the sense of I want
to celebrate, you know,

01:05:24.650 --> 01:05:26.860
or I want to, this reward happened,

01:05:26.860 --> 01:05:29.480
I want to put more reward on there.

01:05:29.480 --> 01:05:31.250
And it's really really fascinating

01:05:31.250 --> 01:05:34.060
because when people
come to that realization

01:05:34.060 --> 01:05:37.430
about themselves, that
they're most vulnerable

01:05:37.430 --> 01:05:41.860
when things are going well,
that's really a valuable insight

01:05:41.860 --> 01:05:43.890
because then they can
put some things in place

01:05:43.890 --> 01:05:46.200
or barriers in place
or go to more meetings

01:05:46.200 --> 01:05:48.170
or whatever it is that they do, you know,

01:05:48.170 --> 01:05:50.350
to protect themselves.

01:05:50.350 --> 01:05:53.910
- Along those lines, I have
a friend 40 years sober,

01:05:53.910 --> 01:05:57.080
was a severe drug and alcohol
addict from a very young age.

01:05:57.080 --> 01:05:58.080
Really impressive person,

01:05:58.080 --> 01:06:00.240
does a lot of important
work in the kind of

01:06:00.240 --> 01:06:02.600
at-risk youth community out in Hawaii.

01:06:02.600 --> 01:06:05.060
And he said something to me, he said,

01:06:05.060 --> 01:06:09.340
as former addicts often do,
they've got these great sayings.

01:06:09.340 --> 01:06:11.250
But I think it fits very well
with what you're describing.

01:06:11.250 --> 01:06:14.380
He said, you know, no
matter how far you drive,

01:06:14.380 --> 01:06:17.640
you're always the same
distance from the ditch.

01:06:17.640 --> 01:06:20.460
And I said well that's kind
of depressing, and he said no,

01:06:20.460 --> 01:06:22.477
that's actually what gives me peace.

01:06:22.477 --> 01:06:23.310
- Yeah.

01:06:23.310 --> 01:06:24.500
- Because what would happen is

01:06:24.500 --> 01:06:27.697
for so many years of
relapsing and relapsing,

01:06:27.697 --> 01:06:32.697
recovering and relapsing, he
felt like it was hopeless.

01:06:33.270 --> 01:06:36.080
And then somehow conceptualizing that

01:06:36.080 --> 01:06:38.870
the vigilance can never go away,

01:06:38.870 --> 01:06:40.730
instead of making him feel burdened,

01:06:40.730 --> 01:06:43.040
- Yeah.
- it made him feel relieved.

01:06:43.040 --> 01:06:46.120
So I often think about
that statement, you know,

01:06:46.120 --> 01:06:47.330
no matter how far you drive,

01:06:47.330 --> 01:06:48.880
you're always the same
distance from the ditch,

01:06:48.880 --> 01:06:51.020
because in my mind I
conceptualize that as gosh,

01:06:51.020 --> 01:06:53.800
that's a tough way to drive down the road.

01:06:53.800 --> 01:06:57.310
But actually, on a road where
you know where the ditch is

01:06:57.310 --> 01:06:59.280
and where you know where
the lanes lines are,

01:06:59.280 --> 01:07:01.000
it's actually a pretty nice drive.

01:07:01.000 --> 01:07:02.610
It's when you don't know
where the shoulder is,

01:07:02.610 --> 01:07:04.250
that you constantly have
to be looking around.

01:07:04.250 --> 01:07:07.678
So there's this, we're
speaking now in analogies

01:07:07.678 --> 01:07:11.450
and imagery and science.

01:07:11.450 --> 01:07:14.320
But I, one of the things
I find so incredible

01:07:14.320 --> 01:07:16.340
about this community of 12-step,

01:07:16.340 --> 01:07:19.024
and there are a variety of them,

01:07:19.024 --> 01:07:22.513
are the communities that
they create for themselves,

01:07:23.480 --> 01:07:27.260
and some of these sayings,
which I do believe link back

01:07:27.260 --> 01:07:29.333
to really core biological mechanisms.

01:07:29.333 --> 01:07:30.370
- Yes, yes.

01:07:30.370 --> 01:07:32.480
- I do want to ask
about those communities.

01:07:32.480 --> 01:07:36.870
I have a question which might
be a little bit controversial.

01:07:36.870 --> 01:07:37.703
- Great!

01:07:37.703 --> 01:07:41.620
- Which is, is it possible that people

01:07:41.620 --> 01:07:44.240
who were addicted to drugs
or alcohol or gambling,

01:07:44.240 --> 01:07:46.040
or some other behavior,

01:07:46.040 --> 01:07:49.210
get addicted to the addiction community?

01:07:49.210 --> 01:07:53.480
Because one thing that I
think I observe over and over

01:07:53.480 --> 01:07:56.550
is that there's some circuit
in the brain of human beings

01:07:56.550 --> 01:07:58.820
that has to tell you about

01:07:58.820 --> 01:08:01.643
the dream they had the night
before, for whatever reason.

01:08:02.580 --> 01:08:06.150
There's another circuit that
leads people to wake you up,

01:08:06.150 --> 01:08:07.470
if they themselves can't sleep.

01:08:07.470 --> 01:08:08.930
I don't know what circuit it is.

01:08:08.930 --> 01:08:10.360
I'm being facetious here.

01:08:10.360 --> 01:08:13.100
But there does seem to also be a circuit

01:08:13.100 --> 01:08:17.480
in the brain of addicts
to discuss and want to

01:08:18.590 --> 01:08:21.710
kind of talk about their recovery a lot.

01:08:21.710 --> 01:08:23.930
And I mention this not to poke at them,

01:08:23.930 --> 01:08:25.320
but rather the opposite,

01:08:25.320 --> 01:08:29.300
because I think that one
thing that is challenging,

01:08:29.300 --> 01:08:32.160
at least for me, and having
friends that have a propensity

01:08:32.160 --> 01:08:34.120
for drug or alcohol
addiction, not all of them,

01:08:34.120 --> 01:08:35.520
but certainly some of them,

01:08:35.520 --> 01:08:37.530
is when they're talking
about their recovery,

01:08:37.530 --> 01:08:40.800
I feel like it's all they talk about.

01:08:40.800 --> 01:08:43.647
This meeting, that meeting, that meeting.

01:08:44.920 --> 01:08:48.060
So what I'm really asking here is that,

01:08:48.060 --> 01:08:51.563
can we become addicted to sobriety?

01:08:52.720 --> 01:08:53.720
- Right.

01:08:53.720 --> 01:08:56.300
So this is a great
question and it links into

01:08:56.300 --> 01:08:58.490
some of the other things
we've been talking about,

01:08:58.490 --> 01:09:01.660
having to do with where do
we settle out, you know?

01:09:01.660 --> 01:09:04.570
What is the way to live
between pleasure and pain?

01:09:04.570 --> 01:09:06.630
And I implied earlier that

01:09:06.630 --> 01:09:08.660
ultimately we want a resilient balance

01:09:08.660 --> 01:09:10.240
that's sensitive to pleasure and pain,

01:09:10.240 --> 01:09:14.300
but that can easily restore
homeostasis after we indulge,

01:09:14.300 --> 01:09:16.283
even when we indulge greatly.

01:09:17.160 --> 01:09:18.920
But the truth of the matter is that

01:09:18.920 --> 01:09:20.830
people with severe addiction,

01:09:20.830 --> 01:09:25.240
I believe temperamentally
want those extremes,

01:09:25.240 --> 01:09:28.530
and they're wired for
that kind of intensity

01:09:28.530 --> 01:09:31.410
that is more than just
these slight adjustments

01:09:31.410 --> 01:09:32.530
around the fulcrum, right?

01:09:32.530 --> 01:09:35.120
It's like they want the
big highs and the big lows.

01:09:35.120 --> 01:09:36.560
- They'll say great meeting.

01:09:36.560 --> 01:09:37.393
- Yeah, right, right.
- They're like

01:09:37.393 --> 01:09:38.226
that was such an amazing meeting.

01:09:38.226 --> 01:09:40.274
Or they find a group,
- Right, yeah.

01:09:40.274 --> 01:09:41.130
- They find a group in a location.

01:09:41.130 --> 01:09:42.460
- Yeah.

01:09:42.460 --> 01:09:44.700
- This is almost an inside
joke in those communities.

01:09:44.700 --> 01:09:45.840
Again, I'm not reporting,

01:09:45.840 --> 01:09:47.440
I'm not talking about a friend in quotes,

01:09:47.440 --> 01:09:48.759
this isn't me reporting.

01:09:48.759 --> 01:09:51.883
They'll talk about how
attractive people are

01:09:51.883 --> 01:09:54.740
at a given meeting, or
how bonded they feel

01:09:54.740 --> 01:09:55.910
to people at a given meeting.
- Right, right.

01:09:55.910 --> 01:09:57.990
- That the meetings themselves

01:09:57.990 --> 01:09:59.410
- Right.
- become their own form

01:09:59.410 --> 01:10:00.243
of dopamine hit.

01:10:00.243 --> 01:10:01.520
- Yes, yes, yes.

01:10:01.520 --> 01:10:03.760
- And again, I'm not
being disparaging, I just,

01:10:03.760 --> 01:10:04.880
I want to understand this.

01:10:04.880 --> 01:10:08.610
- Right, so yes, so a lot of
times patients will say to me,

01:10:08.610 --> 01:10:10.290
oh, you know, I don't want to go to AA.

01:10:10.290 --> 01:10:11.240
It's a cult.

01:10:11.240 --> 01:10:12.830
And my response to that is

01:10:13.780 --> 01:10:18.600
because it's a cult is
exactly why it works, okay.

01:10:18.600 --> 01:10:23.600
Because yes, it is much better
for you to be addicted to AA

01:10:23.720 --> 01:10:24.840
and to recovery,

01:10:24.840 --> 01:10:28.450
than almost any other
addiction I could think of.

01:10:28.450 --> 01:10:31.670
And we know from Rob Malenka's
work, who's here at Stanford,

01:10:31.670 --> 01:10:33.980
that oxytocin, you know,

01:10:33.980 --> 01:10:37.340
is the hormone that's
involved in human pair bonding

01:10:37.340 --> 01:10:39.950
and relationships and love.

01:10:39.950 --> 01:10:42.580
And it directly links to dopamine neurons

01:10:42.580 --> 01:10:44.030
and causes the release of dopamine.

01:10:44.030 --> 01:10:46.700
So yes, when we connect with other humans,

01:10:46.700 --> 01:10:49.490
especially in a kind of
transcendent spiritual way,

01:10:49.490 --> 01:10:51.050
that's a huge dopamine hit.

01:10:51.050 --> 01:10:54.160
And it does replace the dopamine
that people get from drugs.

01:10:54.160 --> 01:10:58.420
And for people who have
this addiction temperament,

01:10:58.420 --> 01:11:00.810
they need it on a more intense level.

01:11:00.810 --> 01:11:05.180
They're not going to be
generally satisfied with kind of,

01:11:05.180 --> 01:11:08.750
you know, a sort of
acquaintanceship, right?

01:11:08.750 --> 01:11:11.940
They want that intensity of
the intimacy that you get

01:11:11.940 --> 01:11:15.490
with people when you're
cathartically exposing, you know,

01:11:15.490 --> 01:11:16.600
warts and all.

01:11:16.600 --> 01:11:19.210
So yes, people can get
addicted to recovery,

