Well why, right?

01:22:11.370 --> 01:22:14.500
And there's really interesting
neuroscience behind it

01:22:14.500 --> 01:22:17.680
that suggests that when we tell the truth,

01:22:17.680 --> 01:22:19.900
we actually potentially strengthen

01:22:19.900 --> 01:22:22.580
our prefrontal cortical circuits,

01:22:22.580 --> 01:22:24.800
and their connections to our limbic brain

01:22:24.800 --> 01:22:26.090
and our reward brain.

01:22:26.090 --> 01:22:28.410
And of course, these are the
circuits that get disconnected

01:22:28.410 --> 01:22:29.940
when we're in our addiction, right?

01:22:29.940 --> 01:22:32.580
Our balance, in our reward
pathway, our limbic brain,

01:22:32.580 --> 01:22:34.270
our emotion brain, is doing one thing,

01:22:34.270 --> 01:22:35.820
and our cortical circuits

01:22:35.820 --> 01:22:37.430
are completely disengaged from that,

01:22:37.430 --> 01:22:38.450
ignoring what's happening,

01:22:38.450 --> 01:22:40.440
which is easy to do
because it's reflexive.

01:22:40.440 --> 01:22:42.740
We don't need to think about that balance

01:22:42.740 --> 01:22:44.490
for the balance to be happening.

01:22:44.490 --> 01:22:47.120
But we have to re-engage those circuits,

01:22:47.120 --> 01:22:49.370
anticipate future consequences,

01:22:49.370 --> 01:22:51.340
think through the drink, you know,

01:22:51.340 --> 01:22:54.050
not just how am I going
to feel now if I use,

01:22:54.050 --> 01:22:56.780
but how am I going to feel
tomorrow or six months from now?

01:22:56.780 --> 01:23:00.470
And that telling the truth
is in fact a way to do that,

01:23:00.470 --> 01:23:02.390
to make these connections stronger.

01:23:02.390 --> 01:23:04.700
And there I talk about
some studies in my book

01:23:04.700 --> 01:23:06.780
that kind of indirectly show that.

01:23:06.780 --> 01:23:08.120
So I find that really fascinating,

01:23:08.120 --> 01:23:12.310
plus just that like being
open and honest with people

01:23:12.310 --> 01:23:16.610
really does create very
intimate connections,

01:23:16.610 --> 01:23:20.450
and those intimate
connections create dopamine.

01:23:20.450 --> 01:23:21.870
So we were talking a little bit about

01:23:21.870 --> 01:23:23.710
how you know a bunch of people

01:23:23.710 --> 01:23:26.170
who need like intensity in their lives.

01:23:26.170 --> 01:23:31.110
For me, I need a lot of intensity
in my human connections.

01:23:31.110 --> 01:23:33.130
Like I'm really not interested in,

01:23:33.130 --> 01:23:38.130
and bored by and made anxious
by, casual interactions.

01:23:39.410 --> 01:23:41.970
But you know, like having this
kind of discussion with you,

01:23:41.970 --> 01:23:46.360
that's very intense and also
intimate and self-disclosing,

01:23:46.360 --> 01:23:47.870
is very rewarding for me.

01:23:47.870 --> 01:23:49.520
So that's an important source of dopamine.

01:23:49.520 --> 01:23:51.079
Thank God I became a psychiatrist.

01:23:51.079 --> 01:23:52.310
- Yeah, absolutely.

01:23:52.310 --> 01:23:53.860
- Like I can't disclose all my stuff,

01:23:53.860 --> 01:23:55.900
but I am quite transparent
with my patients,

01:23:55.900 --> 01:23:57.723
which is a slightly unorthodox.

01:23:58.630 --> 01:24:00.110
But, you know, when I think it's right,

01:24:00.110 --> 01:24:01.550
I'm also transparent with them.

01:24:01.550 --> 01:24:04.010
So that's, you know, that's
a source of dopamine too,

01:24:04.010 --> 01:24:06.690
when we're honest and we disclose.

01:24:06.690 --> 01:24:08.400
You think people are going
to run away from you,

01:24:08.400 --> 01:24:10.520
if you tell them about all
like your weird neuroses,

01:24:10.520 --> 01:24:11.880
but really they don't.

01:24:11.880 --> 01:24:13.200
What they're like is oh thank God,

01:24:13.200 --> 01:24:15.270
I'm not the only one, right.

01:24:15.270 --> 01:24:17.790
- What I love about, I love
many things about your book.

01:24:17.790 --> 01:24:19.330
I read it in one sweep.

01:24:19.330 --> 01:24:20.163
- Oh thank you.

01:24:20.163 --> 01:24:21.333
- And I was like wow.

01:24:24.290 --> 01:24:27.430
I was pleasantly surprised,
but I was like wow,

01:24:27.430 --> 01:24:29.530
she's really opening up in this book,

01:24:29.530 --> 01:24:30.743
from the very beginning.

01:24:31.730 --> 01:24:34.810
And I don't want to give
it away, but it's yeah,

01:24:34.810 --> 01:24:38.670
you're very open where it's appropriate.

01:24:38.670 --> 01:24:43.670
And also I think that this
question about truth-telling,

01:24:44.250 --> 01:24:47.690
I always think about like tell the truth,

01:24:47.690 --> 01:24:50.290
be a hundred percent about the truth,

01:24:50.290 --> 01:24:52.870
but there's also this element about

01:24:52.870 --> 01:24:57.530
do you report previous lies, right?

01:24:57.530 --> 01:24:59.820
What about prior behavior?

01:24:59.820 --> 01:25:02.490
And I'm fascinated by this
'cause to me telling the truth

01:25:02.490 --> 01:25:07.140
has many facets, but the
three sides of this thing

01:25:07.140 --> 01:25:10.860
in my mind, are one is
reporting everything accurately.

01:25:10.860 --> 01:25:12.590
The other is what do you withhold,

01:25:12.590 --> 01:25:14.360
what do you not withhold, right?

01:25:14.360 --> 01:25:16.560
Because some people say tell the truth,

01:25:16.560 --> 01:25:17.800
or at least don't lie.

01:25:17.800 --> 01:25:19.250
That's sort of a-

01:25:19.250 --> 01:25:20.083
- Lies of omission, right.

01:25:20.083 --> 01:25:21.313
- Yeah, so lies of omission.

01:25:22.210 --> 01:25:23.570
Lies of omission.

01:25:23.570 --> 01:25:28.070
And then there's the, what I
have to assume for most people,

01:25:28.070 --> 01:25:31.490
is a small to enormous batch of things

01:25:31.490 --> 01:25:33.680
that they lied about in the past,

01:25:33.680 --> 01:25:35.781
that still thread into the future.

01:25:35.781 --> 01:25:36.614
- Right.

01:25:36.614 --> 01:25:38.680
- So how important is it for the addict,

01:25:38.680 --> 01:25:41.510
or every person really, to,

01:25:41.510 --> 01:25:43.300
'cause it sounds like
cultivating the circuitry

01:25:43.300 --> 01:25:45.380
between prefrontal cortex
and the dopamine system

01:25:45.380 --> 01:25:47.010
would be great for anybody.

01:25:47.010 --> 01:25:48.120
Since we're all addicts,

01:25:48.120 --> 01:25:49.180
- Right.
- everyone should do it.

01:25:49.180 --> 01:25:50.720
But in all seriousness,

01:25:50.720 --> 01:25:53.360
it sounds like a good
thing for everybody to do.

01:25:53.360 --> 01:25:58.360
How much work needs to be
done on all the priors,

01:25:58.680 --> 01:26:00.643
all the stuff we've hidden?

01:26:02.230 --> 01:26:03.900
I mean not me, but all the stuff

01:26:03.900 --> 01:26:05.570
that everybody else has hidden.

01:26:07.130 --> 01:26:10.180
- Yeah, so the, you know,

01:26:10.180 --> 01:26:14.160
the steps of the 12-steps
of Alcoholics Anonymous,

01:26:14.160 --> 01:26:17.660
a good number of those steps
are about that very thing.

01:26:17.660 --> 01:26:20.920
The past, the ways that we've
harmed people in the past.

01:26:20.920 --> 01:26:25.293
And the fourth step is
about making amends,

01:26:26.600 --> 01:26:29.140
you know, by admitting the ways in which

01:26:29.140 --> 01:26:33.640
that we've contributed to harming others.

01:26:33.640 --> 01:26:36.570
And it is a really big piece of recovery.

01:26:36.570 --> 01:26:39.920
So, you know, how important,
so for people with addiction,

01:26:39.920 --> 01:26:43.160
it's really, really important
to go back and make amends.

01:26:43.160 --> 01:26:47.960
And, you know, the key idea there is

01:26:47.960 --> 01:26:50.260
you just go back and
you apologize, you know,

01:26:50.260 --> 01:26:53.910
and you don't have to get any
particular kind of response,

01:26:53.910 --> 01:26:55.490
or you don't need to be forgiven.

01:26:55.490 --> 01:26:59.200
It's the act itself of apologizing

01:26:59.200 --> 01:27:01.650
about the ways in which we've harmed

01:27:01.650 --> 01:27:04.730
or lied to people in the past,

01:27:04.730 --> 01:27:07.640
that is cathartic and renewing,

01:27:07.640 --> 01:27:09.910
and allows us to kind of shed this skin

01:27:09.910 --> 01:27:12.590
and be new in our lives and begin again.

01:27:12.590 --> 01:27:16.593
Sort of absolved, you know,
of past sins, so to speak.

01:27:17.450 --> 01:27:19.113
So it is really important.

01:27:20.300 --> 01:27:21.510
You know, are there situations

01:27:21.510 --> 01:27:23.140
when it's maybe not a good idea,

01:27:23.140 --> 01:27:26.260
because of that person or the nature?

01:27:26.260 --> 01:27:28.720
Sure, you know, there
are always going to be,

01:27:28.720 --> 01:27:30.130
it doesn't have to be like, it's not,

01:27:30.130 --> 01:27:32.420
we're talking about not
like Kant's idea about

01:27:32.420 --> 01:27:35.210
I'd never lie, robbers in your house.

01:27:35.210 --> 01:27:36.220
You're a stowaway.

01:27:36.220 --> 01:27:37.053
You can't lie even about that.

01:27:37.053 --> 01:27:39.906
It's like no, there are
probably situations where,

01:27:39.906 --> 01:27:41.220
- Absolutely.
- you know.

01:27:41.220 --> 01:27:42.650
- For sake of other people's safety,

01:27:42.650 --> 01:27:43.650
- Right, and-
- children's safety, sure.

01:27:43.650 --> 01:27:45.130
- Right, I mean there are,

01:27:45.130 --> 01:27:47.279
you can think of a million scenarios.

01:27:47.279 --> 01:27:51.540
But in general, you know,
when we're taking stock,

01:27:51.540 --> 01:27:52.610
because I don't know about you,

01:27:52.610 --> 01:27:55.090
but I have a lot of regrets and guilt

01:27:55.090 --> 01:27:57.350
about a lot of things in my life.

01:27:57.350 --> 01:28:02.350
And they kind of haunt me, you know.

01:28:02.873 --> 01:28:05.090
It means I'll have nightmares, right.

01:28:05.090 --> 01:28:06.607
And I think that's true for most people.

01:28:06.607 --> 01:28:08.753
I mean I occasionally will
meet somebody who's like

01:28:08.753 --> 01:28:11.310
I don't have any regrets
in my life, I'm like wow.

01:28:11.310 --> 01:28:14.533
Like I cannot relate to that at all.

01:28:15.768 --> 01:28:20.210
So, you know, this idea of
like catharsis and, well,

01:28:20.210 --> 01:28:22.610
I mean, in the 12-steps it's telling God,

01:28:22.610 --> 01:28:25.300
or your higher power,
telling another human being,

01:28:25.300 --> 01:28:26.940
the ways in which you've wronged others.

01:28:26.940 --> 01:28:28.870
Considering your own character defects

01:28:28.870 --> 01:28:29.950
and how those have contributed.

01:28:29.950 --> 01:28:31.580
To me, that's a really important piece

01:28:31.580 --> 01:28:33.590
and something that we don't do enough

01:28:33.590 --> 01:28:35.070
in our current culture.

01:28:35.070 --> 01:28:36.560
Especially in psychiatry, frankly,

01:28:36.560 --> 01:28:37.570
where there's like a lot of

01:28:37.570 --> 01:28:40.350
eternally empathizing with patients,

01:28:40.350 --> 01:28:42.500
but not a whole lot of
likes going well, you know,

01:28:42.500 --> 01:28:44.320
actually you kind of messed that up.

01:28:44.320 --> 01:28:48.146
Or like that was really
bad on you, you know.

01:28:48.146 --> 01:28:50.580
And in my work, I don't
necessarily use that language,

01:28:50.580 --> 01:28:52.910
but, you know, patients might say like

01:28:52.910 --> 01:28:55.390
I really feel badly about,
you know, this thing.

01:28:55.390 --> 01:28:57.380
I'll be like yeah, I get it.

01:28:57.380 --> 01:28:59.140
I understand that you feel.

01:28:59.140 --> 01:29:00.248
- Well guilt is a-

01:29:00.248 --> 01:29:01.081
- [Anna] Right.

01:29:01.081 --> 01:29:01.980
- There's a circuit for that too.

01:29:01.980 --> 01:29:04.390
- Right, and it's important, right,

01:29:04.390 --> 01:29:07.550
and it's also important to recovery

01:29:07.550 --> 01:29:09.013
and to not becoming addicted.

01:29:09.013 --> 01:29:12.810
Experiencing a certain
amount of appropriate shame

01:29:12.810 --> 01:29:15.620
for things that we have
done and, you know,

01:29:15.620 --> 01:29:18.700
feeling the pain that comes with shame,

01:29:18.700 --> 01:29:20.887
which is an incredibly
painful emotion, right.

01:29:20.887 --> 01:29:23.080
And I think that may be the
one that we all try to avoid

01:29:23.080 --> 01:29:24.370
more than any other,

01:29:24.370 --> 01:29:28.830
is like that shame of not being
liked or not being accepted

01:29:28.830 --> 01:29:31.029
or not being celebrated.
- Or the thing that we did

01:29:31.029 --> 01:29:32.940
is really despicable.

01:29:32.940 --> 01:29:34.770
- Right, it's really,
yeah, like oh my God,

01:29:34.770 --> 01:29:37.370
I did that horrible thing, right, right.

01:29:37.370 --> 01:29:39.350
So, I mean, I've done horrible things

01:29:39.350 --> 01:29:43.220
that I haven't gone back and
said I did this horrible thing,

01:29:43.220 --> 01:29:45.630
but I'm, maybe I've
tried to pay it forward.

01:29:45.630 --> 01:29:47.070
Like I've told my kids, you know,

01:29:47.070 --> 01:29:49.420
when I was younger I
did this horrible thing

01:29:49.420 --> 01:29:50.980
and it still haunts me.

01:29:50.980 --> 01:29:54.120
So if you're ever tempted to
do something like what I did,

01:29:54.120 --> 01:29:56.010
you might think about my situation.

01:29:56.010 --> 01:29:57.820
So, you know, some kind of way.

01:29:57.820 --> 01:30:00.243
But I think wrestling
with that is important.

01:30:01.180 --> 01:30:03.190
- I think it's a really
important element to all this,

01:30:03.190 --> 01:30:07.080
and there's not, I love that
there's neuroscience being done

01:30:07.080 --> 01:30:07.913
on truth-telling,

01:30:07.913 --> 01:30:08.810
- Yeah.
- and the value

01:30:08.810 --> 01:30:09.643
of truth-telling.

01:30:09.643 --> 01:30:10.476
- Yeah.
- I think,

01:30:11.770 --> 01:30:15.870
if I were to predict a new
and truly exciting area

01:30:15.870 --> 01:30:17.808
that people are going to
be really curious about,

01:30:17.808 --> 01:30:20.900
in this huge sphere we call neuroscience,

01:30:20.900 --> 01:30:22.870
I hope they'll continue to do more work.

01:30:22.870 --> 01:30:26.380
Also, I'm so glad to hear that's
