01:33:47.006 --> 01:33:49.290
that helps me think about this is

01:33:49.290 --> 01:33:51.510
there are many ways to
the top of the mountain,

01:33:51.510 --> 01:33:54.200
and these are sort of
like taking the gondola

01:33:54.200 --> 01:33:56.020
instead of walking up.

01:33:56.020 --> 01:33:58.180
It sort of, instead of doing like

01:33:58.180 --> 01:33:59.710
a year of psychoanalysis

01:33:59.710 --> 01:34:01.460
where you're sitting
on the couch every week

01:34:01.460 --> 01:34:03.210
reflecting on your life,

01:34:03.210 --> 01:34:07.080
it's a condensed version of
psychoanalysis or psychotherapy,

01:34:07.080 --> 01:34:10.990
plus, you know, MDMA, which
gets you there faster.

01:34:10.990 --> 01:34:13.590
- And creates the intimacy,
presumably, because of the-

01:34:13.590 --> 01:34:16.440
- Well I think the main thing that happens

01:34:16.440 --> 01:34:21.060
when it's beneficial, is
it just allows the person

01:34:21.060 --> 01:34:26.060
to get outside of their own
head and look at their lives

01:34:26.300 --> 01:34:31.270
on a much broader sweep,
and to consider themselves

01:34:31.270 --> 01:34:36.270
not mired in the quotidian
sort of details of their life,

01:34:37.230 --> 01:34:42.230
but rather as a human on
the large planet Earth,

01:34:42.350 --> 01:34:43.980
in the vast universe.

01:34:43.980 --> 01:34:47.930
So I think it takes,
it's like when it works,

01:34:47.930 --> 01:34:50.290
it's a transformational experience

01:34:50.290 --> 01:34:54.840
because it gives the person another lens

01:34:54.840 --> 01:34:58.180
through which to view their lives,

01:34:58.180 --> 01:35:02.040
which I think for some people
is positive and powerful,

01:35:02.040 --> 01:35:04.490
because they can come
back from that and be like

01:35:04.490 --> 01:35:08.370
oh my gosh, I care about my family,

01:35:08.370 --> 01:35:10.940
and I don't, I want X, Y, or Z for them.

01:35:10.940 --> 01:35:13.583
And I realize that my continuing to drink

01:35:13.583 --> 01:35:15.410
is not going to, you know, achieve that.

01:35:15.410 --> 01:35:20.060
So it's almost like a
spiritual or values-based.

01:35:20.060 --> 01:35:23.430
So I think it can be very
powerful, but having said that,

01:35:23.430 --> 01:35:27.490
I truly am quite skeptical
because, you know,

01:35:27.490 --> 01:35:30.160
addiction is a chronic
relapsing and remitting problem.

01:35:30.160 --> 01:35:31.150
It's hard for me to imagine

01:35:31.150 --> 01:35:34.700
that there's something that
works very quickly short-term,

01:35:34.700 --> 01:35:39.050
that's going to work for a disease
that's really long-lasting.

01:35:39.050 --> 01:35:41.258
- Yeah, the two addicts I know that did

01:35:41.258 --> 01:35:45.510
MDMA-assisted psychotherapy
as part of this thing,

01:35:45.510 --> 01:35:46.710
both got worse.

01:35:46.710 --> 01:35:48.270
- Yeah.

01:35:48.270 --> 01:35:52.650
- But the people I know who
had severe trauma who did this,

01:35:52.650 --> 01:35:55.170
who took this approach,
seem to be doing better.

01:35:55.170 --> 01:35:56.913
- Okay, interesting.
- And so I,

01:35:57.860 --> 01:36:00.590
I think that the discussion,
as we hear it now,

01:36:00.590 --> 01:36:03.760
is just sort of psychedelics,
which is a huge category

01:36:03.760 --> 01:36:06.180
that includes many different
drugs and compounds

01:36:06.180 --> 01:36:07.290
with different effects.

01:36:07.290 --> 01:36:11.500
And we hear about trauma and
addiction lumped together.

01:36:11.500 --> 01:36:14.920
And I think that I'm a
splitter, not a lumper,

01:36:14.920 --> 01:36:16.223
as we say in science.

01:36:19.090 --> 01:36:22.550
And I think it's going to be
important for people to know

01:36:22.550 --> 01:36:26.890
that this is definitely
not a one-size fits all

01:36:26.890 --> 01:36:28.150
kind of thing.

01:36:28.150 --> 01:36:30.200
But it sounds like it
may have some utility

01:36:30.200 --> 01:36:31.710
under certain conditions.

01:36:31.710 --> 01:36:33.347
- Yeah, I think so.

01:36:33.347 --> 01:36:35.380
I'm trying to be very open-minded

01:36:35.380 --> 01:36:38.480
about its potential utility
for certain individuals.

01:36:38.480 --> 01:36:40.450
But I can tell you in my clinical work,

01:36:40.450 --> 01:36:43.990
what is a very concerning
unintended consequence

01:36:43.990 --> 01:36:45.750
of this narrative,

01:36:45.750 --> 01:36:48.640
is I have a lot of people who
are looking for some kind of

01:36:48.640 --> 01:36:51.070
spiritual awakening who on their own,

01:36:51.070 --> 01:36:53.470
not in the context of
any kind of therapeutic,

01:36:53.470 --> 01:36:55.130
psychological work, you know,

01:36:55.130 --> 01:37:00.130
microdose or want to try
psilocybin or MDMA with a friend

01:37:01.100 --> 01:37:03.770
or wherever, so they can have
this spiritual experience

01:37:03.770 --> 01:37:05.390
that they can figure out their lives.

01:37:05.390 --> 01:37:09.280
That's a disaster and
almost never works out well.

01:37:09.280 --> 01:37:11.240
And I've then had people who literally,

01:37:11.240 --> 01:37:15.210
supposedly you can't get
addicted to psychedelics because,

01:37:15.210 --> 01:37:16.520
you know, something with the biochemistry

01:37:16.520 --> 01:37:17.510
which I don't fully understand,

01:37:17.510 --> 01:37:18.940
'cause it doesn't make any sense to me.

01:37:18.940 --> 01:37:20.410
But I have patients clinically

01:37:20.410 --> 01:37:22.800
who definitely are addicted to,

01:37:22.800 --> 01:37:24.870
you know, MDMA, to micro-dosing.

01:37:24.870 --> 01:37:28.480
So that's very concerning
to me 'cause like, you know,

01:37:28.480 --> 01:37:30.230
Pollan's "How to Change Your Mind",

01:37:32.070 --> 01:37:35.400
I respect that work, but on
the other hand, it's penetrated

01:37:35.400 --> 01:37:36.650
the culture-
- Michael Pollan's book.

01:37:36.650 --> 01:37:37.483
- [Anna] Yeah, yeah.

01:37:37.483 --> 01:37:40.952
- And I don't know him and
so I don't have a problem

01:37:40.952 --> 01:37:43.250
taking a stance.

01:37:43.250 --> 01:37:45.280
So I'll just say my stance on that is

01:37:45.280 --> 01:37:49.230
the narrative of popular authors

01:37:49.230 --> 01:37:52.190
can expand and wick out so fast,

01:37:52.190 --> 01:37:53.023
- Yes.

01:37:53.023 --> 01:37:54.410
- that pretty soon people are essentially

01:37:54.410 --> 01:37:56.840
taking their mental health
into their own hands.

01:37:56.840 --> 01:38:00.970
And I actually, I have great
optimism for this business

01:38:00.970 --> 01:38:05.970
of clinical use of
psychedelics, including MDMA.

01:38:07.010 --> 01:38:08.750
Matthew Johnson at Johns Hopkins

01:38:08.750 --> 01:38:10.683
is doing fabulous work on this.

01:38:11.570 --> 01:38:13.830
And there are others too, of course.

01:38:13.830 --> 01:38:15.878
But those are controlled settings.

01:38:15.878 --> 01:38:16.711
- Right.

01:38:16.711 --> 01:38:18.040
- And the pharmacology is being tuned up.

01:38:18.040 --> 01:38:20.540
And one thing that I think is coming.

01:38:20.540 --> 01:38:22.660
There are several papers
published recently

01:38:22.660 --> 01:38:25.483
in great journals like nature
and science, et cetera,

01:38:26.620 --> 01:38:30.150
where there are scientists
who are removing

01:38:30.150 --> 01:38:33.310
the hallucinogenic
components of these drugs

01:38:34.160 --> 01:38:38.893
and finding that they still
have the antidepressant effects.

01:38:38.893 --> 01:38:40.680
- Interesting.
- And so the experience

01:38:40.680 --> 01:38:42.570
of a psychedelic,

01:38:42.570 --> 01:38:45.040
and the long-term effects
of the psychedelic,

01:38:45.040 --> 01:38:47.510
might actually be dissociable.

01:38:47.510 --> 01:38:50.520
And so, again I, and I'm
always careful to say

01:38:50.520 --> 01:38:53.340
I'm neither for something or against it.

01:38:53.340 --> 01:38:58.340
I just think that treading
carefully is what's important.

01:38:58.510 --> 01:39:01.440
- I agree with you, and
I can just tell you that

01:39:01.440 --> 01:39:05.183
the downstream effect
for the average person,

01:39:07.010 --> 01:39:09.490
many of whom present in our clinic,

01:39:09.490 --> 01:39:12.730
is that they've misconstrued the data

01:39:12.730 --> 01:39:16.503
on the use of psychedelics
for mental health conditions,

01:39:17.450 --> 01:39:19.460
to this idea that they're safe,

01:39:19.460 --> 01:39:21.590
or that anybody can take
them in any circumstance

01:39:21.590 --> 01:39:23.470
and have this kind of awakening.

01:39:23.470 --> 01:39:26.540
And that's not what the data show, right?

01:39:26.540 --> 01:39:30.451
The data are these highly
controlled settings, you know,

01:39:30.451 --> 01:39:32.470
carefully selected patients.

01:39:32.470 --> 01:39:34.700
So that's my worry, you know.

01:39:34.700 --> 01:39:35.533
- Sure.

01:39:35.533 --> 01:39:38.020
And I'm going to be sitting
down with Matthew Johnson

01:39:38.020 --> 01:39:40.070
at some point, and we'll discuss this.

01:39:40.070 --> 01:39:45.070
And I think that, ah,
that care and that cocoon

01:39:45.088 --> 01:39:47.660
of real clinical care, does seem to be

01:39:47.660 --> 01:39:49.720
an important component.
- Yes.

01:39:49.720 --> 01:39:52.610
- Well I'm glad we could
touch on it and, you know,

01:39:52.610 --> 01:39:53.860
I'm sure I'll get a bunch of comments

01:39:53.860 --> 01:39:55.583
telling me that, you know.

01:39:57.130 --> 01:39:59.140
But I think it is
important to explore things

01:39:59.140 --> 01:40:01.400
from all sides, and that's what we do,

01:40:01.400 --> 01:40:02.250
as scientists.
- Yes.

01:40:02.250 --> 01:40:05.630
- And if Michael Pollan wants
to chat, we can do that too.

01:40:05.630 --> 01:40:07.089
That's fine.

01:40:07.089 --> 01:40:07.922
I very much enjoyed the book

01:40:07.922 --> 01:40:08.890
actually.
- Yes, yes.

01:40:08.890 --> 01:40:12.430
- But I think that people run with ideas.

01:40:12.430 --> 01:40:13.263
- That's right.

01:40:13.263 --> 01:40:14.096
- They don't walk with them,

01:40:14.096 --> 01:40:15.523
they sprint.
- That's right, right.

01:40:15.523 --> 01:40:16.625
Yeah.

01:40:16.625 --> 01:40:19.890
- There are a couple other
things I just want to touch on,

01:40:19.890 --> 01:40:22.010
but they all relate to social media.

01:40:22.010 --> 01:40:22.843
- [Anna] Okay.

01:40:22.843 --> 01:40:25.230
- You were featured in
"The Social Dilemma".

01:40:25.230 --> 01:40:26.310
It was a powerful movie.

01:40:26.310 --> 01:40:28.310
I think many people
avoided seeing that movie

01:40:28.310 --> 01:40:32.160
because it reflects back on us
just how addicted we all are

01:40:32.160 --> 01:40:34.138
and how manipulated we all are.

01:40:34.138 --> 01:40:34.971
- [Anna] Yes.

01:40:34.971 --> 01:40:38.100
- But it doesn't seem to
have changed behavior much.

01:40:38.100 --> 01:40:40.010
I have to say that the movie

01:40:40.010 --> 01:40:42.540
changed my understanding
and my perception,

01:40:42.540 --> 01:40:44.553
but not my behavior too much.

01:40:46.460 --> 01:40:48.680
If we look at addiction
as a maladaptive thing,

01:40:48.680 --> 01:40:50.690
something that's making our lives worse

01:40:50.690 --> 01:40:54.900
or us less functional at
work and in relationships,

01:40:54.900 --> 01:40:57.160
I could imagine a version of social media

01:40:57.160 --> 01:40:59.810
where it's making me more connected.

01:40:59.810 --> 01:41:00.817
I mean this is a podcast after all.

01:41:00.817 --> 01:41:02.820
- Yes, yes.
- I post videos.

01:41:02.820 --> 01:41:04.100
This will show up on YouTube

01:41:04.100 --> 01:41:08.050
and elements of it on Instagram as well.

01:41:08.050 --> 01:41:12.420
So much like sugar or other things,

01:41:12.420 --> 01:41:15.260
I have to imagine that
we need to regulate,

01:41:15.260 --> 01:41:18.400
not necessarily eliminate, this behavior.

01:41:18.400 --> 01:41:20.750
So I want to talk about
what that looks like.

01:41:20.750 --> 01:41:23.750
And I want to talk about
what you've referred to

01:41:23.750 --> 01:41:26.940
as this narcissistic preoccupation

01:41:26.940 --> 01:41:28.800
that social media is creating.

01:41:28.800 --> 01:41:33.570
That we are all far more
keenly aware of how we look

01:41:33.570 --> 01:41:36.910
and how we sound and how
we are being perceived,

01:41:36.910 --> 01:41:39.912
than we were 10 years ago.

01:41:39.912 --> 01:41:40.745
- [Anna] Right.

01:41:40.745 --> 01:41:45.745
- So first of all, social media,
how addicting is it really?

01:41:46.040 --> 01:41:50.343
And what is healthy social media behavior?

01:41:51.270 --> 01:41:56.270
- So the first message I
would want to get across

01:41:56.560 --> 01:41:59.660
about social media, is
that it really is a drug

01:41:59.660 --> 01:42:02.023
and it's engineered to be a drug.

01:42:02.950 --> 01:42:07.950
And it's based on, you know,
potency, quantity, variety,

01:42:07.990 --> 01:42:10.210
the bottomless polls, the likes,

01:42:10.210 --> 01:42:12.800
the way that it's enumerated, all of that.

01:42:12.800 --> 01:42:16.220
Which doesn't mean that we can't use it,

01:42:16.220 --> 01:42:19.500
but we need to be very thoughtful
about the way we use it,

01:42:19.500 --> 01:42:21.210
just like we need to be thoughtful about

01:42:21.210 --> 01:42:23.033
the way we use any drug.

01:42:24.431 --> 01:42:28.600
And so that means with
intention and in advance,

01:42:28.600 --> 01:42:30.770
planning our use, right.

01:42:30.770 --> 01:42:35.650
And trying to use it as
a really awesome tool

01:42:35.650 --> 01:42:38.270
to potentially connect with other people,

01:42:38.270 --> 01:42:43.160
and not to be used by
it or get lost in it.

01:42:43.160 --> 01:42:44.420
And of course, you know,

01:42:44.420 --> 01:42:47.540
people are going to come
with different propensities

01:42:47.540 --> 01:42:49.560
for addiction to any drug,

01:42:49.560 --> 01:42:51.090
and that's true for social media too.

01:42:51.090 --> 01:42:54.750
Some people will have no
problem using it in moderation

01:42:54.750 --> 01:42:56.440
or using it in a way that's adaptive.

01:42:56.440 --> 01:43:00.340
And other people will
immediately get sucked in.

01:43:00.340 --> 01:43:02.360
And the key thing about
getting addicted is

01:43:02.360 --> 01:43:05.330
when it's happening, nobody
who's getting addicted

01:43:05.330 --> 01:43:06.550
thinks they're getting addicted, right.

01:43:06.550 --> 01:43:10.000
Let's face it, it's only after
the fact that we go woops,

01:43:10.000 --> 01:43:11.180
you know, what was that about?

01:43:11.180 --> 01:43:12.670
- Remember texting and driving,

01:43:12.670 --> 01:43:14.460
there are all these books
about texting and driving,

01:43:14.460 --> 01:43:15.670
how terrible it was.

01:43:15.670 --> 01:43:16.503
- Yeah.

01:43:16.503 --> 01:43:18.560
- Even the governments
have largely given up.

01:43:18.560 --> 01:43:20.200
You see these billboards

01:43:20.200 --> 01:43:21.650
- Terrifying.
- like don't text and drive,

01:43:21.650 --> 01:43:23.090
or any text can wait, or whatever.

01:43:23.090 --> 01:43:24.966
Not worth dying for.

01:43:24.966 --> 01:43:25.799
- Right, right.
- But everybody's

01:43:25.799 --> 01:43:26.690
texting and driving.

01:43:26.690 --> 01:43:28.180
- Right and if you look at
young people today, teenagers,

01:43:28.180 --> 01:43:30.640
I mean they're basically
cybernetically enhanced,

01:43:30.640 --> 01:43:32.150
that the phone is there.

01:43:32.150 --> 01:43:33.830
You know, it's like they're talking to you

01:43:33.830 --> 01:43:36.360
and texting 12 friends at the same time,

01:43:36.360 --> 01:43:37.950
and there's no stopping it.

01:43:37.950 --> 01:43:40.620
I mean the genie is out of
the bottle where, you know,

01:43:40.620 --> 01:43:41.610
we're not going back.

01:43:41.610 --> 01:43:42.470
- [Andrew] Right.

01:43:42.470 --> 01:43:45.010
- So we do need to figure out, you know,

01:43:45.010 --> 01:43:50.010
how to make this tool
something that's, you know,

01:43:50.120 --> 01:43:52.950
going to be good for us
and not ultimately harmful.

01:43:52.950 --> 01:43:55.220
And I don't have all the answers

01:43:55.220 --> 01:43:58.930
by any stretch of the imagination,
but I do think, you know,

01:43:58.930 --> 01:44:01.260
some of the wisdom that we have learned

01:44:01.260 --> 01:44:05.220
from using other drugs, also
applies to social media.

01:44:05.220 --> 01:44:07.830
Which is to say that we have to, again,

01:44:07.830 --> 01:44:10.520
put barriers in place that allow us

01:44:10.520 --> 01:44:14.440
to remain in control of our
use, which means not too much,

01:44:14.440 --> 01:44:17.760
you know, not too often, not too potent.

01:44:17.760 --> 01:44:19.900
- Do you think in, going
back to this idea of

01:44:19.900 --> 01:44:23.460
the unit of the day being
a good attractable unit,

01:44:23.460 --> 01:44:25.973
a manageable unit of time for most people,

01:44:26.840 --> 01:44:29.780
so you're saying in advance,
so allocating two hours

01:44:29.780 --> 01:44:33.310
in which you're going to
allow yourself to have

01:44:33.310 --> 01:44:34.427
free reign use of the phone

01:44:34.427 --> 01:44:35.970
and all its apps and all its things,

01:44:35.970 --> 01:44:39.910
or even more restricted
than that, meaning okay,

01:44:39.910 --> 01:44:42.360
I'm only going to allow
myself 30 minutes a day

01:44:42.360 --> 01:44:46.760
to post and comment, and then
that's a closeout completely.

01:44:46.760 --> 01:44:49.210
- Yeah, so I think it's,
it depends on the person

01:44:49.210 --> 01:44:50.110
and sort of a combination.

01:44:50.110 --> 01:44:51.300
We talked earlier about, you know,

01:44:51.300 --> 01:44:53.570
having an itch and
scratching yourself at night.

01:44:53.570 --> 01:44:55.330
We've gotten to a point with smartphones,

01:44:55.330 --> 01:44:56.930
people are pulling them out

01:44:56.930 --> 01:44:59.310
and they are utterly
unconscious of doing so,

01:44:59.310 --> 01:45:02.060
pulling them out, you know,
a couple of texts, a couple.

01:45:02.060 --> 01:45:03.002
They don't know

01:45:03.002 --> 01:45:03.835
they're doing it!
- I have a friend

01:45:03.835 --> 01:45:06.680
