01:51:50.390 --> 01:51:52.290
into things that we care about.

01:51:52.290 --> 01:51:55.240
And if our competence in
that arena is threatened,

01:51:55.240 --> 01:51:57.340
we would all experience
a narcissistic injury,

01:51:57.340 --> 01:51:59.403
and that's normal and healthy.

01:52:00.344 --> 01:52:04.370
But we are living in a
narcissistic culture,

01:52:04.370 --> 01:52:05.640
I mean that's not news,

01:52:05.640 --> 01:52:08.870
this preoccupation with
individual achievement

01:52:08.870 --> 01:52:12.870
and individual self-worth and
individual self-confidence.

01:52:12.870 --> 01:52:17.870
And I think all of that is
just fueled by social media,

01:52:17.890 --> 01:52:19.810
where we're not just seeing ourselves,

01:52:19.810 --> 01:52:21.920
but we're seeing people's
reactions to ourselves,

01:52:21.920 --> 01:52:24.780
and every single, you know,
thing we say or do, you know,

01:52:24.780 --> 01:52:26.840
we get likes and this and that.

01:52:26.840 --> 01:52:30.160
It's really insidious and
it contributes, I think,

01:52:30.160 --> 01:52:33.120
ultimately to a lot of personal shame,

01:52:33.120 --> 01:52:36.780
because we're not really
meant to be individuals

01:52:36.780 --> 01:52:38.390
bouncing around in the universe.

01:52:38.390 --> 01:52:40.010
We're social animals.

01:52:40.010 --> 01:52:43.000
And we're probably generally happiest,

01:52:43.000 --> 01:52:45.720
even for natural contrarians among us,

01:52:45.720 --> 01:52:48.220
when we're part of a tribe, right.

01:52:48.220 --> 01:52:51.330
And if we do too much to
kind of separate ourselves

01:52:51.330 --> 01:52:53.520
from that tribe,

01:52:53.520 --> 01:52:56.430
I think that the brain's natural

01:52:56.430 --> 01:52:59.170
and instinctive corrective
mechanism against that

