do my startup, go to Africa,

01:57:13.110 --> 01:57:14.230
apply for that grant?

01:57:14.230 --> 01:57:15.520
You know, it's like, really,

01:57:15.520 --> 01:57:17.720
I was just trying to
learn how to be a doctor.

01:57:17.720 --> 01:57:20.700
And it's, as you say, it's
a lot of pressure on them.

01:57:20.700 --> 01:57:24.650
And it's also kind of a weird leapfrogging

01:57:24.650 --> 01:57:28.720
of the real way to accomplish something.

01:57:28.720 --> 01:57:30.880
- Right.
- Which isn't about like

01:57:30.880 --> 01:57:32.010
oh how can I accomplish something.

01:57:32.010 --> 01:57:36.360
It's like, what can I do today
that would be of service.

01:57:36.360 --> 01:57:37.193
Right?

01:57:37.193 --> 01:57:41.100
And then finding that of trying
to be of service, you know,

01:57:41.100 --> 01:57:43.380
and not really going for recognition,

01:57:43.380 --> 01:57:46.210
can sometimes lead to
what people call success,

01:57:46.210 --> 01:57:47.900
although that wasn't
what you were aiming for.

01:57:47.900 --> 01:57:49.270
- And it's all the more beautiful

01:57:49.270 --> 01:57:50.570
when it's not what you're aiming for.

01:57:50.570 --> 01:57:52.600
- Oh so much better, so much better.

01:57:52.600 --> 01:57:55.480
- Yeah, I'm a big
believer that when one can

01:57:56.760 --> 01:58:00.480
align their compulsion
with some greater good.

01:58:00.480 --> 01:58:02.540
- Yes, right.
- A service to humanity

01:58:02.540 --> 01:58:05.163
or the planet or animals, whatever it is,

01:58:06.346 --> 01:58:09.760
that's where the really
good stuff emerges.

01:58:09.760 --> 01:58:11.730
Because there's a lot
of reciprocity there.

01:58:11.730 --> 01:58:14.800
The world starts to,
you're supporting the world

01:58:14.800 --> 01:58:16.760
and then it starts to support you in a way

01:58:16.760 --> 01:58:18.850
that feels very fluid.
- And it comes back.

01:58:18.850 --> 01:58:20.120
Right, and I mean that speaks to you

01:58:20.120 --> 01:58:24.320
like your generosity to
me, vis-a-vis my book.

01:58:24.320 --> 01:58:25.153
And I have to say-

01:58:25.153 --> 01:58:26.180
- Well, I love the book.

01:58:26.180 --> 01:58:27.013
- I know, it's-

01:58:27.013 --> 01:58:28.880
- There's like, we're not
in a business deal folks.

01:58:28.880 --> 01:58:31.710
It's just purely that I heard
Anna lecture in my course,

01:58:31.710 --> 01:58:33.180
I wanted to learn more about dopamine.

01:58:33.180 --> 01:58:34.013
She taught me,

01:58:34.013 --> 01:58:35.070
I asked her if she would
come on the podcast.

01:58:35.070 --> 01:58:36.770
Turned out she wrote this amazing book.

01:58:36.770 --> 01:58:38.870
She sent me an advanced copy of the book.

01:58:38.870 --> 01:58:41.180
I read it in one sweep, it's incredible.

01:58:41.180 --> 01:58:42.013
And I love it.

01:58:42.013 --> 01:58:45.290
So just like the eight
year old version of me,

01:58:45.290 --> 01:58:48.260
now the 45 version of myself,

01:58:48.260 --> 01:58:50.510
I can't stop blabbing
about the things I love.

01:58:50.510 --> 01:58:52.570
- Well it's awesome, but I have to say,

01:58:52.570 --> 01:58:56.740
I have been surprised by your generosity.

01:58:56.740 --> 01:59:01.740
It's not something I've
encountered frequently at Stanford,

01:59:02.010 --> 01:59:03.170
which is a wonderful place.

01:59:03.170 --> 01:59:08.170
But there is a general
sense that if I give away

01:59:10.290 --> 01:59:14.383
to somebody else, I've lost something,

01:59:16.060 --> 01:59:18.350
which is not the right
way to think about it.

01:59:18.350 --> 01:59:21.630
Not how you are, and also
not how the world works,

01:59:21.630 --> 01:59:24.230
